{"name":"Power Modifiers","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_3t20aa8en26","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Power Modifiers</h2>\n<p>Power Modifiers allow characters to customize their abilities, adding a special effect that better reflects her @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Powers]{power's} @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trapping}.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Power Modifiers are selected each time a power is activated and may be freely changed each time. An icy @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} might cause @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{Armor Piercing} damage in one attack and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Lingering Damage (+2)]{Lingering Damage} in the next.</p>\n<p>A number of common modifiers are listed below, and some powers have additional options as well. The number in parentheses is the price in additional @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Points} it costs to add the effect.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Casters} must declare which modifiers they&rsquo;re using before rolling their arcane skill.</p>\n<p>Unless a modifier says otherwise, it may be applied to any power, but only once per casting.</p>\n<p>Power Modifiers last for the Duration of the spell, or until the end of the target&rsquo;s next turn in the case of Instant powers.</p>\n<h3>Modifiers</h3>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Add Armor Piercing]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cause Lingering Damage]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Change Duration]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Extend Range]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatiguing]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon Strength]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hinder or Hurry]</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Selective Targets]</strong></p>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Articles on the Use of Magic</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Powers Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rituals]{Rituals}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/tiefling.webp\" alt=\"Tiefling spellcaster\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"C7WsurU1ajOBLdZw"}
{"name":"Arcane Background (Divine Magic)","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_e33lugmfz55","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Divine Magic)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Divine Magic)]{Arcane Background (Divine Magic)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} d8+, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Faith]{Faith}&nbsp;d4+</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Faith]{Faith}&nbsp;(@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Miracles:</strong> Clerics and paladins may take Edges that require @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Background (Miracles)}.</li>\n<li><strong>Transgressions:&nbsp;</strong>Clerics and paladins who violate the tenets of their faith can get blocked from thier source of power. Consult each deity for what are considered transgressions and the effects.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash:&nbsp;</strong>When a member of the clergy rolls a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Faith]{Faith} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3 (one signature power, plus two of player's choice)</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers: </strong>Very depending on the deity or faith followed.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Divine Magic</h2>\n<p>There&rsquo;s no logic to divine magic, no pure science that can explain exactly how it works. An acolyte might spend years meditating and praying, performing virtuous deeds, and tending their flock, and still never gain the power to cast a spell; meanwhile, a smith who can&rsquo;t even read might feel @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onator]{Onatar&rsquo;s} guiding hands and cast magecraft. Divine magic requires two things: absolute faith and a connection to a divine power source.</p>\n<p>Faith is about conviction. It can&rsquo;t be something you approach rationally. You need to know in your heart that the magical effect you seek to produce with your spell should and will happen. Whether you&rsquo;re smiting an enemy or healing an ally, you know that the enemy will fall and that you will save your friend. This doesn&rsquo;t mean that you have to be a zealot with no doubts whatsoever; you can question your overall course of action. But you can&rsquo;t think about your doubts in the moment of casting the spell; in that instant, you must have pure and absolute certainty that the spell will come to pass.</p>\n<h3>Connection to Divine Power</h3>\n<p>But faith alone isn&rsquo;t enough; you also need a connection to a source of divine power. In Eberron, no one can prove whether the Sovereigns or other deities exist&mdash;if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onatar]{Onatar} actually guides all artisans or if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Dorn]{Dol Dorn} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} truly watch over every battlefield. But whether or not @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} exists, when her paladin smites a foe, they draw that power from something. The paladin believes it to be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} granting her favor, and maybe it is. Or maybe the shared faith of the tens of thousands of people who believe in the Sovereigns has created wells of power in the collective unconscious, and the paladin draws on this powerful force instead. In a practical sense, the truth is irrelevant; regardless of its nature and source, the power exists. And this is where science fails. The Silver Flame is a source of divine power, a force that has held demons at bay for millennia. Those who seek to defend the innocent and fight supernatural evil can draw on its power. But why does one templar become a paladin over another of equal faith? Why does an illiterate farmer gain the gift of divine magic when a religious scholar who&rsquo;s spent decades studying texts doesn&rsquo;t? People of faith usually respond that it&rsquo;s because the farmer was chosen by Arawai, or because one templar was more open than the other to the Voice of the Flame. Maybe that&rsquo;s true, or maybe it&rsquo;s all just luck.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>To the outside observer, divine magic is very different in flavor from arcane magic. A wizard traces glowing sigils and speaks words in a language older than humanity; a priest simply points dramatically at their enemy and calls on the Silver Flame to strike them down. Whether a spell is fueled by arcane or divine power, however, it still requires verbal and somatic components. Practically speaking, this means the spellcaster has to be able to speak and use their hands, and that these are somehow tied to casting a spell. But where a wizard may recite a complex incantation, the verbal component of divine magic could be the simplest of prayers: &ldquo;@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} smite my foe!&rdquo; or &ldquo;Stand revealed in the light of the Flame!&rdquo; Or it might be more complex, perhaps singing a hymn or reciting a passage from an ancient text. In both cases, the verbal components are statements of conviction and intent. Just as arcane magic is more than words and gestures, divine magic likewise has a mental component. The caster doesn&rsquo;t just ask for something; they reach out and take the power from the divine source, and if they draw too heavily on this connection, it can backlash on them.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings} for divine magic vary greatly depending on the faith or diety of the the clergy. A follower of the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Devourer]{Devourer} <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>might be a shock of lightning while a&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>from a disciple of the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Silver Flame]{Silver Flame} might manifest as a silvery flame. View the specific suggestions on the various deities or faiths.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"DgoZWeay3KCM1dkQ"}
{"name":"Half-orc","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hXW8dnse3pIGZnz5"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Half-orc</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Thousands of years beforc humans came to Khorvaire, the land was dominated by wild orcs and goblinoids of the Dhakaani Empire. The goblin empire scattered the orc tribes and forced them into harsh and unwanted lands: the swamps of the Shadow Marches, the Demon Wastes, and the depths of the Ironroot Mountains. But in the Shadow Marches, the orcs learned the secrets of druidic magic from the dragon Vvaraak, becoming the first of the Gatekeepers. With the invasion of the alien daelkyr from Xoriat, the Gatekeepers put the dragon's teaching to the test, creating magical seals that bound the daelkyr in the depths of Khyber and protected Eberron against further incursion from the plane of madness.</p>\n<p>Three prominent groups of orcs have survived into the present age:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Ghaash'kala are servants of the Silver Flame (which they call Kalok Shash, the \"binding flame\"), who devote their lives to battling the fiends of the Demon Wastes. Humans from the Carrion Tribes of the wastes sometimes hear the call ofKalok Shash and join the Ghaash'kala, leading to a significant population of half-orcs there.</li>\n<li>The Jhorash'tar orcs are a perpetual threat in and around the Ironroot Mountains, shaped by their resentment of the Mror dwarves who drove them underground. These orcs are isolated from humans, so half-orcs here are rare.</li>\n<li>The Shadow Marches holds the largest numbers of orcs and the most significant population of half-orcs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Orcs of the Shadow Marches</h3>\n<p>The orc Gatekeepers played a crucial role in defeating the daelkyr and binding their evil in Khyber, and their descendants continue to maintain the ancient seals and fight aberrations spawned by the daelkyr's corruption. However, many orcs succumbed to that same corruption and embraced the madness of the cults of the Dragon Below. orcs who follow both of these paths continue to live in the Shadow Marches, and centuries of battles between them have diminished both sides.</p>\n<p>Humans settled in the Shadow Marches long ago, and the first half-orcs helped to cement the bond between these outsiders and the native orcs. Certain Marcher clans contain humans, orcs, and half-orcs in roughly equal numbers.</p>\n<p>When playing an orc or half-orc character from the Shadow Marches, consider what circumstances brought you into the wider world. The Leaving the Shadow Marches table offers some inspiration.</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs of Khorvaire</h3>\n<p>With the rise ofthe dragonmarked House Tharashk, ores and half-orcs have spread through the Five Nations and beyond. In general, the people of the Five Nations know little about half-ores. When people imagine a half-orc, they usually think of a Tharashk bounty hunter or dogged inquisitive, but a few ignorant sorts might still hold the stereotype of a \"simpleton from the swamps.\"</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>Mark of Finding</em> appears among half-orcs of House Tharashk. Dragonmarked half-orcs work extensively with humans, orcs, and unmarked half-orcs in pursuit of the house's mission of bounty hunting, inquisitive work, and prospecting. Across Khorvaire, anyone who wants to find something or someone turns to House Tharashk.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Heritage: </strong>Half-orcs may retain the strength of their orc parent or the adaptability of their human ancestry. A half-orc may either start with a free @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice} @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Edges]{Edge} of his choice <em>or</em> a d6 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4 (which also increases his @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} maximum to d12+1).</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Half-orcs start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Orcish}.</li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision: </strong>Half-orcs have the eyesight of their orc heritage. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Primal Intuition: </strong>Half-orcs start with a d4 in one of the following skills: @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}<em>, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Healing]{Healing}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice}, </em>or @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Survival]{Survival}. If the chosen skill is a core skill, it starts at d6 and the skill's maximum increases to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/half-orc.webp\" alt=\"Dragonmarked member of House Tharashk\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/half-orc.webp","_id":"DvW48gwVGtE1InPo"}
{"name":"Races","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_jtibz2gzdj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"header\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p>Races</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><cite>Savage Eberron</cite> has the following races that are available for play as player characters. All races are balanced out to +4 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Making Races]{racial abilities} instead of the usual +2.</p>\n<h2>Races</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bugbear]{Bugbear}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Changeling]{Changeling}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dwarf]{Dwarf}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Elf]{Elf}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Gnome]{Gnome}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Goblin]{Goblin}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Half-elf]{Half-elf}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Half-orc]{Half-orc}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Halfling]{Halfling}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hobgoblin]{Hobgoblin}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Human]{Human}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Kalashtar]{Kalashtar}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Orc]{Orc}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shifter]{Shifter}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Warforged]{Warforged}</h3>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Exotic Races</h2>\n<p>The following races are far more exotic and rare in Eberron. These require DM approval for particular campaigns.</p>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Elf, Drow]{Elf, Drow}: Xen'drik</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Eneko]{Eneko}: Sarlona</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Half-giant]{Half-giant}: Sarlona and Xen'drik</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Tiefling]{Tiefling}: Generally rare</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"Ef2dc5ieLzUF3Q5s"}
{"name":"Archeologist","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hW3xL2LcVGgDuDwA"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>An archaeologist learns about the long-lost and fallen cultures of the past by studying their remains -their bones, their ruins, their surviving masterworks, and their tombs. Those who practice archaeology travel to the far corners of Eberron to root through crumbled cities and lost dungeons, digging in search of artifacts that might tell the stories of monarchs and high priests, wars and cataclysms, and most importantly, their magic and technology.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Language, Lore, Notice, Persuasion, Religion, Research, Science, Shooting, Stealth, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Brave, Linguist</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Artifact Hunter, Explorer, Investigator, Scholar, Thief</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Scavenger</p>","_id":"EjxNeGAbkirBgwTg"}
