{"name":"Bounty Hunter","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.G4Pzh2XyhAw9EiYp"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>The most reputable bounty hunters in Khorvaire are members of House Tharashk’s Finders Guild. Still others might operate independently to avoid the strict policies and procedures imposed by House Tharashk, but competition with the Finder’s Guild is stiff.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Healing, Intimidation, Shooting, Survival, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Luck</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Calculating, Level Headed</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Escape Artist, Explorer, Investigator, Jack-of-all-Trades</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Streetwise</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Danger Sense, Scavenger</p>","_id":"IBtAhU4ArkthDtDs"}
{"name":"Shifter","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.P8nuLccu1LyBzOL3"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Shifter</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Shifters are sometimes called the weretouched, as many believe they are the descendants of humans and lycanthropes. Whatever their origins, shifters have evolved into a unique race. They are humanoids with a bestial aspect; while they can't fully change shape, they can temporarily enhance their animalistic features-a state they call shifting. Each shifter walks on the knife's edge between the wilds and the world around them. Do they embrace their primal instincts or the path of civilization?</p>\n<h3>The Beast Within</h3>\n<p>Early in childhood, a shifter forms a bond with a beast within, a totemic force that shapes their body and mind. Some shifters believe that these spirits are independent entities, and they may speak of Bear or Wolf as ancestors or guides. Most just see the beast within as a formidable expression of their inner nature, something that emerges as the shifter's personality takes shape. The beast within is a pool of powerful instincts, and its influence is revealed by a shifter's personality: a feline shifter may be cool and distant, driven by predatory instincts, while a shifter with a lupine spirit might be drawn to find and protect a pack. When a shifter fully embraces this beast within they physically transform for a short time.</p>\n<p>A shifter's beast within is reflected by its shifting ability. Four kinds are especially common:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beasthide </strong>often signifies the bear or boar: stoic, stubborn, and thick-skinned.</li>\n<li><strong>Longtooth </strong>shifters typically have lupine traits and prefer to run with a pack.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftstride </strong>are often predatory and feline, but a swiftstride could also be a cunning rat who darts through the shadows.</li>\n<li><strong>Wildhunt </strong>shifters are born from any creature that tracks its prey.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These other types are also present in the shifter population</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Cliffwalk </strong>often signifies apes, monkeys, or goats: expert climbers and social.</li>\n<li><strong>Dreamsight </strong>don't have a particular beast within, so much as a deep intuitive connection with all beasts.</li>\n<li><strong>Gorebrute </strong>are born from powerful horned beasts.</li>\n<li><strong>Razorclaw </strong>are often clawed predatory animals, often feline in connection.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftwing </strong>are flight beasts such as flying rodents and bats.</li>\n<li><strong>Truedive </strong>manifest connections to fish.</li>\n<li><strong>Winterhide </strong>are from creatures that dwell in cold mountain passes: stoic, tough, and often loners.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>While the beast within certainly has a physical impact on a shifter, it has a spiritual and psychological effect, as well. Two beasthide shifters share the same special ability, but if one has the aspect of the boar and the other is more like a bear, they'll be quite different in personality. With any shifter, identifying the beast within is a crucial part of understanding the character.</p>\n<h3>Similiar and Diverse</h3>\n<p>Shifters are similar to humans in height and build but are typically more lithe and flexible. Their facial features have a bestial cast, often with large eyes, flat noses, and pointed ears; most shifters also have prominent canine teeth. They grow fur-like hair on nearly every part of their bodies.</p>\n<p>The traits of the beast within affect a shifter's appearance as well. A swiftstride shifter may have catlike eyes and delicate build, while a beasthide shifter might be a massive brute built like a bear. While a shifter's appearance might remind an onlooker of an animal, they remain clearly identifiable as shifters even when at their most feral.</p>\n<h3>The Journey Yet to Come</h3>\n<p>Shifters have a strong presence in the Eldeen Reaches but can be found in rural areas across Khorvaire, where they often live among humans. While they form powerful bonds to friends and kin, shifters place great value on self-reliance and freedom. It's a shifter proverb to \"always be prepared for the journey yet to come,\" and most shifters strive to be ready for change or opportunity.</p>\n<p>Shifters have a natural inclination toward classes with a primal connection. A shifter barbarian draws their rage from the beast within. A shifter ranger indulges their urge to wander and hunt. A shifter rogue harnesses their own predatory instincts. But shifters can pursue any path or faith.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Keen Senses: </strong>Shifters have heighted senses. They begin with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} skill. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision: </strong>Shifters have the sight of their beastial ancestors who have hunted in the night andtheir eyes amplify light. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim or Dark illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Shifting (Minor Shape Change): </strong>This ability allows a shifter to tap into his lycanthropic heritage. At character creation, the player chooses a shifter ability from the list below. Shifting is a free action and lasts 1 minute or until dismissed as a free action. While in this animal-like form, the shifter can ignore 1 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{wound penalty}. When the shifting ends, the shifter must wait 4 hours before shifting again or suffer a level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} when the second shifting ends. This level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} can only be removed after 4 hours of abstaining from shifting. If the shifter uses this ability again during the recovery time, it inflicts another level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} that requires an additional 4 hours of recovery time.</li>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beasthide:</strong> The skin of beasthide shifters harden, providing @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{Armor} +4.</li>\n<li><strong>Cliffwalk: </strong>The limbs, hands, and feet of cliffwalk shifters become stronger, allowing cliffwalk shifters to add +2 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (climbing) rolls, and climb at their full @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}.</li>\n<li><strong>Dreamsight:</strong> Dreamsight shifters' instincts and awareness become heightened, granting them the <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em> power. The power affects animals of Size +1 or smaller as well as swarms of Small size. Its effects only last while shifting rather than the power's normal duration.</li>\n<li><strong>Gorebrute: </strong>Gorebrute shifters manifest powerful horns that can inflict @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}+d6 damage (see @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons} in Savage Worlds Adventure Edition core rules).</li>\n<li><strong>Longtooth: </strong>The face of a longtooth shifter distorts, growing a canine muzzle full of sharp teeth that cause @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}+d4 damage (see @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}). Longtooth are also particularly fierce and agressive. They start with a d4 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}.</li>\n<li><strong>Razorclaw: </strong>The claws on the hands of razorclaw shifters grow and can be used to make attacks dealing @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}+d4 damage (see @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}). Razorclaw shifters respect little other than physical power. They get a +1 bonus to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftstride:&nbsp;</strong>The legs of swiftstride shifters elongate and they balance on the balls of their feet. Their base @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} increases by 2 and their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running die} increases a die type.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftwing: </strong>The arms of swiftwing shifters grow leather flaps of skin similar to a bat's wings, granting the ability to fly at a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} of 6 per round, and \"run\" for extra movement as usual. Maneuvering uses the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill. These wings can be targeted, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}, or @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled} by foes.</li>\n<li><strong>Truedive: </strong>Truedive shifters grow fins and webs of skin between their toes and fingers. They become aquatic creatures that cannot drown in water, can move their full @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} when @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{swimming}.</li>\n<li><strong>Wildhunt: </strong>Wildhunt shifters' sense of smell becomes more sensitive, providing a +1 bonus to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Survival]{Survival} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>Winterhide: </strong>A winterhide shifter gains a +8 bonus to resist the negative effects of a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Cold]{cold} environment. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Cold]{Cold} damage is also reduced by 8.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/shifter.webp\" alt=\"Fierce Shifter warrior\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/shifter.webp","_id":"IQcsMa3gs9uyzU1Q"}
{"name":"Glory and Infamy","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_v2dfoof50lp","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"header\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p>Glory and Infamy</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Everything living eventually dies. However, while a mortal's flesh may rot off the bone, his name can live forever through his deeds. Skalds and bards sing tales of heroes who perished long ago, keeping the memory of these figures as alive today as it was when they walked Eberron.</p>\n<section class=\"ridged-block-float\">\n<h3>PLAYING A VILLAIN</h3>\n<p>Not every player is going to want to play a hero, and that's fine. After all, we've given the stat blocks for several evil deities, and there's no restriction on characters worshipping them. However, there is a price to pay for villainy.</p>\n<p>Heroes who perform heroic deeds earn bonuses through their elevated Glory&mdash;villains get very little reward for being evil. Of course, to earn Glory a hero has to take great risks and maintain a certain code of conduct, whereas a villain doesn't have that restriction.</p>\n<p>As such, villains are easy to play, but heroes get all the rewards for being \"forced\" to act in a certain manner.</p>\n</section>\n<p>Glory has nothing to do with social standing, wealth, or who one calls friend&mdash;it is a mark of a character's reputation as a hero. A king may be well known across the lands, but that does not make him a hero, nor does it entitle him to become the focus of ballads or epic poems. Only through heroic deeds can a character aspire to enter the history books and oral myths of Rassilon.</p>\n<p>Your hero's Glory starts at zero, but can be affected by his or her actions during the course of the game. The higher your hero's Glory, the more renowned he is across Rassilon and the more benefits he gains.</p>\n<p>Just as Glory define the acts of a hero, so does Infamy define the acts of a villian. Infamy is Glory that has gone into the \"negative\".</p>\n<h3>Glory vs. Rank</h3>\n<p>A hero's Rank is a measure of his experience, although it does incorporate a degree of glory. Rank is a by-product of earning experience in adventures and quests, which aren't always linked to heroic deeds. Sure, the hero may rescue a princess, but the rescue might be fairly mundane and quickly forgotten. Only deeds which attract attention count toward Glory.</p>\n<h2>Gaining Glory</h2>\n<p>Glory is measured in Glory Points. Characters can rise to become famous heroes or slip into mediocrity or do deeds so heinous that they are remembered in Infamy.</p>\n<p>Glory should not be dolled out like candy. It should be earned through heroic endeavors, good roleplaying, and investing heavily in character, not expected just because the hero is a player character.</p>\n<h3>VARIABLE GLORIOUS DEEDS</h3>\n<p>After each adventure, and only when the heroes return to civilization, one of the party may begin telling the tale of their epic battles and heroic deeds. The character makes a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll, modified as below.</p>\n<p>The DM is always free to add positive modifiers for truly heroic actions or based on the character's weaknesses and how he overcame them. Always try to think of how the heroes' true exploits (as opposed to any extra bits they invent) sound as a tale told by skalds. This is important, as it is the listeners on Khorvaire who are effectively granting them Glory.</p>\n<p>Ideally, an extra +1 or +2 should be the maximum. For instance, slaying a dread liche is certainly worthy of praise, but that is already covered in the table. However, lopping off his head with a Called Shot as the killing blow is worth a small modifier, as it's the sort of detail found in epic poems.</p>\n<p>Likewise, a Novice party with a d6 as their highest combat skill (including arcane skills) who slay a bunch of orc warriors in melee without any assistance should be rewarded with a greater chance of fame.</p>\n<p>The DM may also opt to add penalties to reflect weaker opponents (such as unarmed or unarmored orcs) or favorable character circumstances (every hero had a dozen alchemical <em>blast</em> devices on hand).</p>\n<h3>GLORY AWARDS</h3>\n<p>With a success, every hero involved in the action gains 1d6 Glory. A raise increases this to 2d6. Failure earns no bonus or penalty. A critical failure, however, causes the loss of 1d6 Glory, perhaps because the listeners disbelieved the storyteller or doubt the prowess of the party to achieve what they claim. Roll the dice for each individual member of the party earning or losing Glory.</p>\n<p>Glory awards can be altered by the GM, but this should be done only for truly notable actions. Modifiers normally apply solely to individual members of the party, not every member.</p>\n<p>For instance, the hero who delivered the Called Shot to the head, killing the dread liche, should earn a +1 or +2 bonus for his notable deed. This actively encourages use of special maneuvers and imaginative combat, as opposed to the standard \"attack&ndash;damage\" routine.</p>\n<p>Of course, if one hero played little part in the action, perhaps because he was Incapacitated early on or spent the whole time cowering in fear, he should receive less Glory than those who were in the thick of the action. Just because he's a player character and was present does not entitle him to the same reward as those who risked their lives and took part in the bulk of the action.</p>\n<p>Such a hero may roll his dice with a &ndash;3 penalty, for example, possibly earning a small penalty overall with an unlucky roll because of his inaction.</p>\n<h2>Additional Glory Information</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Calculating Glory]</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"KeCw57crYz1tQ6Zw"}
{"name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_e33lugmfz55","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000","name":"4.2. Arcane Backgrounds","children":["WkAQaYluuHPWNKAx","DgoZWeay3KCM1dkQ","FkxXkVOSgjXDfJpj","q3hdsgwk5MnF9Eby","QNR2rNV5WP4zpDD7"],"folderPath":["temp_okfc4yccund","temp_hcpgzvytjr6"]}},"content":"","_id":"KwWl6OpMsSqLTmrs"}
{"name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_53szy0z05dw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.3. Power Modifiers","color":"#000000","name":"4.3. Power Modifiers","children":["fTuyGb1YCtVSQ5ds","1X7vihm25xEYetuY","6BRC8xV2ccr8bAfs","jw01h7JHExJG4SEN","dxVgdLXW7UaaHiyI","0fr0frcxmqTZ64xG","Y9iVOIf1rH5LerbN","t9Lb0IKevtrptI0D"],"folderPath":["temp_okfc4yccund","temp_hcpgzvytjr6"]}},"content":"","_id":"M2bSxV4tOeQaTIlo"}
{"name":"Kalashtar","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.eOQLfdMRa4e43zbF"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Kalashtar</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The kalashtar are a compound people, created from the union ofhumanity and renegade spirits from the plane of dreams-spirits called quori. Kalashtar are often seen as wise, spiritual people with great compassion for others. There is an unmistakable alien quality to the kalashtar, though, as they are haunted by the conflicts of their otherworldly spirits.</p>\n<h3>Bound to Spirits</h3>\n<p>Every kalashtar has a connection to a spirit of light, a bond shared by other members of their bloodline. Kalashtar appear human, but their spiritual connection affects them in a variety of ways. Kalashtar have symmetrical, slightly angular features, and their eyes often glow when they are focused or expressing strong emotions. Kalashtar can't directly communicate with their quori spirits. Rather, they might experience this relationship as a sense of instinct and inspiration, drawing on the memories of the spirit when they dream. This connection grants kalashtar minor psionic abilities, as well as protection from psychic attacks. All of these quori dream-spirits are virtuous, but some are warriors and others are more contemplative. Work together with the DM to determine the nature ofyour linked spirit. Typically, a kalashtar knows the name and nature of their spirit, but some may know nothing of their spirit or the source of their psychic gifts, such as an orphan kalashtar raised among strangers.</p>\n<h3>Hunted by Nightmares</h3>\n<p>The virtuous spirits tied to the kalashtar fled from the dream-realm of Dal Quor to escape evil spirits that dominate it. The rebel quori believe that through meditation and devotion, they can change the fundamental nature of Dal Quor, shifting the balance from darkness to light. Most kalashtar communities focus on acts of devotion known as the Path of Light. But the dark powers of Dal Quor have their own plans for Eberron. Through the force known as the Dreaming Dark, these monsters manipulate the folk of Khorvaire to eliminate kalashtar whenever possible.</p>\n<p>Many kalashtar defend themselves from the Dreaming Dark by focusing on devotion to the Path of Light. Others, though, seek out the agents of the Dreaming Dark and oppose their plans, or protect the innocent however they can. Still other kalashtar grow up isolated, knowing nothing about Dal Quor or the Dreaming Dark. Such orphans might use their abilities for personal gain or otherwise act against the virtuous instincts of their quori spirits; this can cause internal conflicts and violent mood swings.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Dual Mind: </strong>Because of the guidance from the quori spirit with which they are bonded, kalashtar begin play with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Kalashtar start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Quori}.</li>\n<li><strong>Hunted (Major): </strong>Kalashtar are constantly hunted by the Dreaming Dark and the Inspired of Reidra.</li>\n<li><strong>Mental Discipline:</strong> With their connection with their Quori, kalashtar are incredibly disciplined mentally. They recieve a +1 bonus to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>Mind Link: </strong>Kalashtar have the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Arcane Background (Psionics)} Edge and begin with the <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Mind Link]{mind link}</em> power as one of their known powers granted by the Edge.</li>\n<li><strong>Naturally Psionic: </strong>Kalashtar begins play with a d4 in the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Psionics]{Psionics}&nbsp;skill. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Psionics]{Psionics}&nbsp;to d12+1.​</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/kalashtar.webp\" alt=\"Kalashtar in front of a his Quori\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/kalashtar.webp","_id":"MAOtpm7i1zWBFRzS"}
{"name":"Gnome","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.E6ZUzftrtdHhbmHC"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Gnome</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The average gnome has a love of knowledge that borders on obsession, a curiosity that admits no limits, and a vast collection of potentially useful information on every personal acquaintance. Most gnomes detest physical violence and prefer to solve their problems with words whether that's a bard's eloquent persuasion, a wizard's words of power, or a rogue's careful threat. They give an initial impression as friendly busybodies, always ready to lend a hand or share a story, while asking questions that tend toward the slightly-too-personal. Often, though, a cheerful and amiable gnome is methodically adding to a mental storehouse of knowledge that might one day provide important leverage.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes of Zilargo</h3>\n<p>To say that every Zil gnome is a ruthless schemer would be a hurtful exaggeration. Intrigue is the favorite pastime of most Zil, though. Every gnome child of Zilargo is taught to manipulate and deceive, and by the time they reach adulthood most have been involved in dozens of schemes and feuds, some ofwhich persist well into adulthood. Even a gnome with a good heart and noble goals-of which there are many-often still prefers to use trickery and cunning rather than the unreliable tools of honesty or brute force.</p>\n<p>Most Zil gnomes belong to the forest gnome subrace. Their natural talent for illusion aids them in trickery and entertaining, and they often use small animals as messengers and guides.</p>\n<p>When you're making a Zil gnome character, consider what kinds of schemes you or your family might be involved in. The Zil Schemes table offers some suggestions, but you should feel free to elaborate on these schemes, even to absurd extremes.</p>\n<p>Additionally, consider your relationship to Zilargo: why you have left, and what ties do you still have to it? Your scheme could provide a good reason for you to leave. Or you could be a sage gathering information for the Library of Korranberg or an investigator sending stories ofyour adventures back to the Korranberg Chronicle. Family is important to the Zil, and you could be pursuing your family's interests. You could even be working for the mysterious Trust, the conspiracy behind the Triumvirate's throne that quietly maintains order in Zilargo. Ifyou are working for the Trust, you could have a specific mission, but you could also be a sleeper agent-gathering information and allies until you're activated and you are put to your intended use.</p>\n<p><strong>Zil Names. </strong>Zil society is divided into major houses, each of which is composed of multiple families. Each gnome carries the name of a house and of a family in addition to a personal name. For example, Alina Lorridan Lyrris and Tallian Talius Lyrris are members of different families (Lorridan and Talius) within House Lyrris. Gnome names are long and lyrical; a Zil proverb claims \"the sweetest song is the name of a friend.\" Personal and clan names are usually at least three syllables long, and there is a strong tradition of alliteration.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>As they have for countless generations, insatiable curiosity and endless opportunity draw gnomes from Zilargo into the wider lands of Khorvaire. Most of these dispersed gnomes find new homes and integrate easily into local cultures. Gnomes can be found in any walk of life, whether they be as merchants, magewrights, scholars, or scoundrels. While the gnomes of the Five Nations aren't as inherently devious as their Zil cousins, they share the Zil emphasis on the importance of family.</p>\n<p>As a gnome character from the Five Nations, you might have a network of connections to the community your grew up in, likely built on the exchange of information. Alternatively, you might seek your own path in life, avoiding the intrigues your cousins adore.</p>\n<h3>Gnomes and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>Mark of Scribing</em> appears among the gnomes of House Sivis. The gnomes of this house were among the first of their kind to leave Zilargo and live in human lands. They love bureaucracy and intrigue as much as the gnomes of their homeland, but they have carefully cultivated a reputation for impartiality and secrecy, since their services rely on trust.</p>\n<p>Today, House Sivis provides avenues of communication across Khorvaire. Translation, mediation, interpreting, and legal advocacy all fall within House Sivis's broad purview, and they maintain the network of message stations that allow cross-continent communication</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Diminutive:</strong> Gnomes average only about three feet tall, reducing their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>Gnome Cunning:&nbsp;</strong>Gnomes are intelligent creatures. They begin play with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Illusionist:</strong> Gnomes inherently have @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Arcane Background (Gifted)]{Arcane Background (Gifted)} and know the <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Illusion]{Illusion} </em>power. They also have a d4 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Focus]{Focus}. They cannot take the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.New Powers]{New Powers Edge} for this racial ability, but they can take @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Gnomes start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Gnomish}.</li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision:</strong> Gnome eyes amplify light. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim or Dark illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced Pace:&nbsp;</strong>Gnomes have short legs compared to human-sized races. Decrease their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} by 1 and their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running die} one die type.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/gnome.webp\" alt=\"Dragonmarked gnome of House Sivis.\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/gnome.webp","_id":"MILhXBlwUyluGlHW"}
{"name":"Priest/Acolyte","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.87vhPveKV00IKJfp"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>It’s important to understand that in Eberron, not all priests can wield divine energies. A priest provides spiritual guidance to a community and congregation and they don’t need magic to do this. An acolyte is a servant in training to a particular faith.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Common Knowledge, Cosmology, Healing, Persuasion, Religion</p>\n<p><strong>Hindrance:</strong> Vow</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles), Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Command, Command Presence, Fervor, Fanaticism, Inspire, Natural Leader</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Holy/Unholy Warrior</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Monster Hunter, Scholar</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolster, Rabble-Rouser, Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Champion, Healer</p>","_id":"MadW6eW3JIjnwAq5"}
{"name":"Orc","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.PIgr30tajsiG03nz"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Orc</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Thousands of years beforc humans came to Khorvaire, the land was dominated by wild orcs and goblinoids of the Dhakaani Empire. The goblin empire scattered the orc tribes and forced them into harsh and unwanted lands: the swamps of the Shadow Marches, the Demon Wastes, and the depths of the Ironroot Mountains. But in the Shadow Marches, the orcs learned the secrets of druidic magic from the dragon Vvaraak, becoming the first of the Gatekeepers. With the invasion of the alien daelkyr from Xoriat, the Gatekeepers put the dragon's teaching to the test, creating magical seals that bound the daelkyr in the depths of Khyber and protected Eberron against further incursion from the plane of madness.</p>\n<p>Three prominent groups of orcs have survived into the present age:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Ghaash'kala are servants of the Silver Flame (which they call Kalok Shash, the \"binding flame\"), who devote their lives to battling the fiends of the Demon Wastes. Humans from the Carrion Tribes of the wastes sometimes hear the call ofKalok Shash and join the Ghaash'kala, leading to a significant population of half-orcs there.</li>\n<li>The Jhorash'tar orcs are a perpetual threat in and around the Ironroot Mountains, shaped by their resentment of the Mror dwarves who drove them underground. These orcs are isolated from humans, so half-orcs here are rare.</li>\n<li>The Shadow Marches holds the largest numbers of orcs and the most significant population of half-orcs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Orcs of the Shadow Marches</h3>\n<p>The orc Gatekeepers played a crucial role in defeating the daelkyr and binding their evil in Khyber, and their descendants continue to maintain the ancient seals and fight aberrations spawned by the daelkyr's corruption. However, many orcs succumbed to that same corruption and embraced the madness of the cults of the Dragon Below. orcs who follow both of these paths continue to live in the Shadow Marches, and centuries of battles between them have diminished both sides.</p>\n<p>Humans settled in the Shadow Marches long ago, and the first half-orcs helped to cement the bond between these outsiders and the native orcs. Certain Marcher clans contain humans, orcs, and half-orcs in roughly equal numbers.</p>\n<p>When playing an orc or half-orc character from the Shadow Marches, consider what circumstances brought you into the wider world. The Leaving the Shadow Marches table offers some inspiration.</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>Mark of Finding</em> appears among orcs of House Tharashk. Dragonmarked orcs work extensively with humans and half-orcs in pursuit of the house's mission of bounty hunting, inquisitive work, and prospecting. Across Khorvaire, anyone who wants to find something or someone turns to House Tharashk.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Brutish Size: </strong>Orcs are naturally strong. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+1 They are larger than humans standing about 6 1/2-7 1/2 feet tall, increasing their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>Primal Brute:&nbsp;</strong>Orcs focus on core strength and fitness over coordination and flexibility. They treat @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} as linked to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} for purposes of Advancement. The character may also resist @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Test]{Tests} with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} if she chooses. Finally, Orcs increase the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Short Range} of any thrown item by +1. Double that for the adjusted @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Medium Range} , and double again for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Long Range}. If a thrown item&rsquo;s Range is 3/6/12, for example, an Orc's Range is 4/8/16.</li>\n<li><strong>Primal Passion (Minor): </strong>Orcs are reactive and driven by a primal passion. They often take action without thinking things through.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Orcs start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Orcish} depending on where they are from.</li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision: </strong>Orc eyes are accustomed hunting at night, having eye's similiar to a cats. They ignore attack penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim or Dark illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/orc.webp\" alt=\"Orc barbarian warrior from the Shadow Marches\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/orc.webp","_id":"PGUq1EevulMlPiTk"}
{"name":"Explorer","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hNHuff7kzRANSTQg"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Many parts of the world of Eberron either still lie unseen by humanoid eyes or have fallen into forgotten ruin, and there are those who crave wandering the breadth of the land to discover—or rediscover—them. Whether motivated by a thirst for knowledge about Eberron’s most ancient civilizations, a hunger for the long-lost secrets of tremendous arcane power, or simply a lust for gold, explorers subject themselves to tremendous danger to achieve their goals.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Arcana, Athletics, Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Notice, Persuasion, Riding, Survival, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Fleet-Footed, Linguist, Luck, Great Luck</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Artifact Huner, Explorer, Investigator, Jack-of-all-Trades</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Danger Sense, Scavenger</p>","_id":"PPKpygcDlcUp7xrZ"}
{"name":"Knight","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.m7XwStWRKJSYManh"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>You belong to an order of knights who have sworn oaths to achieve a certain goal. The nature of this goal depends on the order you serve, but in your eyes it is without question a vital and honorable endeavor. Most of these orders aren't limited to fighting types, but are open to all sorts of folk who are willing to battle and die for the order's cause. Particularly with the prevalence of magic there are some knightly orders that look for battlemages, such as the Knights Arcane of Aundair.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics, Battle, Fighting, Riding, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Hindrance:</strong> Code of Honor</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Brave</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Fast Mount, Mounted Combatant, Steady Hands, Trademark Weapon, Improved Trademark Weapon</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Command, Command Presence, Fervor, Fantaticism, Hold the Line!, Death before Dishonor, Natural Leader, Tactician, Master Tactician</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Knight, Monster Hunter</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolster, Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>","_id":"PYSBtlBkzr3A5sDa"}
{"name":"Arcane Background (Magic)","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_e33lugmfz55","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Magic)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Magic)]{Arcane Background (Magic)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} d8+, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} d4+</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting}&nbsp;(@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts})</li>\n<li><strong>Magic:</strong> Wizards may take Edges that require Arcane Background (Magic).</li>\n<li><strong>School: </strong>The wizard may specialise in an Arcane School of Magic or be a Universalist.</li>\n<li><strong>Spellbooks:</strong> Wizards must keep and maintain spellbooks. There are far more than academic tomes&mdash;they are a source of mystical power and energy.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash:&nbsp;</strong>When a wizard rolls a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Becalm]{Becalm}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bind Entity]{Bind Entity}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bridge]{Bridge}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Creation]{Creation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal]{Detect/Conceal}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dimensional Leap]{Dimensional Leap}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dimensional Space]{Dimensional Space}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Form]{Elemental Form}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Feast]{Feast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Grave Speak]{Grave Speak}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Jet]{Jet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Legerdemain]{Legerdemain}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Rider]{Mind Rider}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Elemental]{Summon Elemental}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Fiend]{Summon Fiend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Tempest]{Tempest}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Ward]{Ward}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Whirlwind]{Whirlwind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zephyr]{Zephyr}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Arcane Magic</h2>\n<p>Arcane magic is a form of science. There are predictable rules that shape reality, and with proper study and force of will, anyone could potentially perform arcane magic. This is what makes arcane magic the foundation of civilization in the Five Nations: it can be taught, and once learned, it is entirely reliable. Arcane magic involves channeling ambient magical energy&mdash;the powers of the planes, the emanations of the Ring of Siberys&mdash;and focusing it to alter reality. The components of a spell&mdash;like verbal incantations, somatic gestures, and focus items&mdash;help this process, but the most important element of spellcasting is mental focus. Though a fighter could perfectly duplicate the words and gestures of a wizard, nothing would happen. You must cast the spell in your mind, harnessing and shaping mystical energy, and this can dangerous and exhausting.</p>\n<p>Spellcasting using Smarts is grounded in knowledge and logic. For these characters, casting a spell is like solving an equation&mdash;harnessing and carefully channeling the precise quantity of mystical energy required to produce the effect you&rsquo;re looking for. A wizard may use words of power and mystic gestures to generate power, while an artificer instead relies on tools. But either way, you fundamentally know what you&rsquo;re doing, which is why both artificers and wizards can prepare new spells each day. Arcane magic is a science, and you&rsquo;re a scientist.</p>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Principles of Arcane Science}</h3>\n<p>Arcane magic involves the manipulation of vast, ambient mystical energies that permeate Eberron. These forces are largely omnipresent and invisible, not unlike gravity; they&rsquo;re fundamental elements of the world, and in the course of time most cultures find some way to harness and manipulate them. Like most forms of science, there are different theories about how this science works, and specifically what force is being manipulated.</p>\n<p>You should consider what school of Arcane Science your wizard comers from and let that influence the kind of casting that your wizard accomplishes.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Siberyan Theory}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Externalist}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Sympathetic Magic}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Dominion Theory}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Fringe Traditions}</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Schools</h3>\n<p>A wizard's intense studies lead him down two paths&mdash;a \"universalist\" who dabbles in all the various \"schools\" of magic, or a \"specialist\" who focuses on a school at the expense of other studies.</p>\n<p>Specialists designate one favored school and two opposition schools from the list below. They gain one free reroll when casting spells from their favored school, but spells cast from their opposition schools suffer a &minus;2 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier}.</p>\n<p>Opposition spells should be marked with an * in the characters power list, like this: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish*}</em>.</p>\n<p>Universalists have no favored or opposed schools, and thus gain none of the advantages or disadvantages of specialists.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Abjuration:</strong> The abjurer uses magic against itself, specializing in defensive magic. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection},&nbsp; @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Ward]{Ward}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Conjuration:</strong> Conjurersfocus on spells to summon magical servants or bend reality to their will. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bind Entity]{Bind Entity}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bridge]{Bridge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Creation]{Creation}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dimensional Leap]{Dimensional Leap}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dimensional Space]{Dimensional Space}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Feast]{Feast}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Elemental]{Summon Elemental}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Fiend]{Summon Fiend}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Divination:</strong> Diviners are masters of remote viewing and prophesies; they use their spells to explore the world. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal]{Detect/Conceal}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Legerdemain]{Legerdemain}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Rider]{Mind Rider}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Enchantment:</strong> The enchanter uses magic to manipulate the minds and perceptions of opponents. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Evocation:</strong> Evokers revel in the raw power of magic; they use spells to create and destroy with equal ease. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Jet]{Jet}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Tempest]{Tempest}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Whirlwind]{Whirlwind}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Illusion:</strong> Illusionists use magic to produce confounding sights, sounds and even smells to baffle and vex their opponents. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Necromancy:</strong> The necromancer commands undead and uses the power of unlife against their enemies. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Grave Speak]{Grave Speak}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Lower Trait}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</span></li>\n<li><strong>Transmutation:</strong> Transmuters use magic to change themselves and the world around them. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Becalm]{Becalm}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost Trait}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zephyr]{Zephyr}.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Spellbooks</h3>\n<p>Wizards spells are based in the arcane science of Eberron and are complex to comprehend. For this reason, each wizard maintains a spellbook with the spells he's translated and aquired. He studies from this book everyday, transscribing their mystical patterns onto his mind.</p>\n<p>The link to this book is far more than wrote memorization&mdash;it is an arcane bond with the power and patterns within. If a wizard doesn't have access to his spellbook, he may continue to cast normally until the next sunset or sunrise (whichever comes first). After that, the magical imprint on his mind fades and he can no longer cast them.</p>\n<p>Wizards may only have one spellbook at a time. The moment they begin transcribing their spells to a new volume, the new tome becomes his spellbook instead.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>Mages must make gestures with at least one free hand and speak aloud various magical words at least at a whisper. If either their hands are bound or they are prevented from speaking, they cannot cast their spells.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>Wizards are some of the most versatile casters in Eberron. There are no limitations on the kinds of trappings that can be utilized by a wizard.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"QNR2rNV5WP4zpDD7"}
{"name":"House Scion","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.SyGFQAUWO5lYWqmd"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Forget the noble families of Galifar—the real power lies in the hands of the dragonmarked houses. You are a member of one of those houses, and though power comes with any number of responsibilities, you welcome your house duties as a reasonable price to pay for the social, political, economic, and magical power to which you are heir.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Common Knowledge, Dragonmark Focus, Persuasion, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Dragonmark), Charismatic, House Scion, Rich, Filthy Rich</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections</p>","_id":"U9TWWJXzhTLy3RFD"}
{"name":"Eneko","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{"Item":["IsbekHb4py8znJkY"]}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.TZdKP8aYcLMkOx4g"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Eneko</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The Eneko of Skyarn are distant descendants of ogres and half-giants. As refugees of the Sundering and subsequent expansion of Riedra, the eneko have now been forced into one of the last free corners of Sarlona. Also known as \"mongrel ogres\", eneko are a true breeding race in their own right with a long and rich cultural heritage.</p>\n<h3>Free People</h3>\n<p>The home of the eneko, Syrkarn, is a sanctuary of freedom, diversity and humility built out of yuan-ti ruins by refugees fleeing the monolithic culture and military of Riedra. Eneko and humans equally make up the vast majority of the loose nation's inhabitants, and the philosophy of the eneko is difficult to separate from the region they call home. Eneko from Syrkarn value community, personal freedom, and honest labour above all.</p>\n<p>Many eneko live in nomadic tribes, and those that make a home in Sykrarn's cities still must contend with the harsh storms of Sarlona and the dangerous ruins left by ancient civilizations. This trains into all eneko a profound respect for the land and its challenges, and hones their almost supernatural resilience to the elements. Eneko travelers are among the most difficult for Riedra's Thousand Eyes to track.</p>\n<h3>Mixed Bloodlines</h3>\n<p>Eneko originated from the pairings of the ogres of Borunan and the nomadic half-giants that wander the continent. According to half-giant legend, their people are the progeny of Sarlona's native humans and giant explorers from Xen'drik. Grandiose eneko may claim that the blood of the ancient human sorcerer kings and the mightiest titans of Xen'drik flows through their veins. While many Riedrans deride the eneko, labelling them \"mongrels\", eneko themselves view the diversity of their heritage as one of their greatest strengths.</p>\n<h3>Dark Magic</h3>\n<p>The arcane power displayed by their legendary forebearers leads many eneko to the study of magic. The cult of Karrak the Final Guardian, a deity sometimes called an aspect of the Keeper, is said to have its origins in the giants of Xen'drik. Riedrans and less trusting Syrk humans claim the cult of Karrak is a convenient front for the practice of dark magic.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Brute Strength:</strong> Eneko are natural strong. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Clumsy: </strong>Eneko are big and clumsy. They suffer a &ndash;1 penalty to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>Eneko Resilience:</strong>&nbsp;Eneko are hardy and resistant to toxins. They gain a +4 bonus to resist the effects of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison}. Damage from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison} is also reduced by 4.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}:&nbsp;</strong>Eneko start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Riedran}.</li>\n<li><strong>Low-Light Vision:&nbsp;</strong>Eneko have the vision of their ogre ancestors. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim or Dark illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>@Item[IsbekHb4py8znJkY]{Outsider (Minor)}:</strong> Most races are frightened by the mixed heritage of eneko, and eneko are rather reserved and wary. They have -2 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} as other races tend to distrust them.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} +1:</strong> Eneko are much larger than humans, standing about 6 &frac12; &minus; 8 feet tall, increasing thier @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size}&nbsp;(and therefore their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1, combined with Brute Strength this increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} to d12+2.</li>\n<li><strong>Sturdy:</strong>&nbsp;Eneko have a rugged physiology. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/eneko.webp\" alt=\"Eneko standing guard with weapon.\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/eneko.webp","_id":"UljWJl3HHbV01jlE"}
{"name":"Inquisitive","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.vHIOvewOSeq7KPfM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Most typically, inquisitives are members of House Medani’s Warning Guild, and sometimes members of House Tharashk. There are more than a handful that work independently, mostly because they’re just that good at what they do. Serving as private investigators and detectives for hire, inquisitives are cunning, perceptive, and resourceful.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Common Knowledge, Dragonmark Focus, Intimidation, Notice, Persuasion, Research, Taunt, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Alertness, Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Detection or Dragonmark of Finding)</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Escape Artist, Investigator</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Menacing, Streetwise</p>","_id":"Un0lcuopqqmHAqZY"}
{"name":"Half-elf","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.FRquWp9XZYIVKyuI"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Half-elf</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>From the Towering Woods of the Eldeen Reaches to the slums of Sham, half-elves are found across Khorvaire. New half-elves are born in every generation from pairings between humans, elves, and other half-elves, with children typically clinging to a parent's culture. Over centuries, though, half-elves have developed their own communities and traditions, giving them an identity strengthened by the rise of House Lyrandar and House Medani. Members of these communities generally dislike the term \"half-elf,\" instead calling themselves Khoravar, an Elvish term meaning \"children of Khorvaire.\"</p>\n<p>The elves of Aerenal have never allowed a half-elf into the Undying Court, and the Valenar elves don't consider half-elves capable of channeling a Valenar ancestral spirit. Among humans, though, half-elves don't experience any more prejudice or bias than members of other races, and some half-elves could easily be mistaken for human.</p>\n<p>In making a half-elf character, consider whether you were born in a Khoravar community, or if your parents were members of different races. Is your half-elf identity a source of pride, a simple fact of life, or something that has been difficult for you?</p>\n<h3>Khorvar</h3>\n<p>The culture that has developed among Khorvaire's native half-elves places a strong emphasis on hospitality toward other Khoravar. They don't expect each other to put themselves in danger for strangers' sake, but when possible, half-elves do what they can to help others with information, shelter, and the like. Khoravar communities have weekly unity dinners where local news and events are shared; these meals are a great chance to hear about local events and opportunities.</p>\n<p>Many Khoravar espouse the idea of \"the bridge between,\" the notion that the Khoravar are called to facilitate communication and cooperation between members of different cultures or species. Khoravar who follow this philosophy often become bards, diplomats, mediators, or translators. Others are fascinated by their distant connection to the fey and seek to build bridges between the Material Plane and the Feywild of Thelanis. These Khoravar often become Greensinger druids or warlocks with Archfey patrons.</p>\n<p>Khoravar speak both Common and Elvish, and among themselves they often blend these two together. This pidgin makes perfect sense to anyone who speaks both languages, but someone who speaks only one of them will miss some words and subtlety of meaning.</p>\n<p>As you create a Khoravar character, you have a wide range of options to describe your backstory. The Khoravar Origin table can provide inspiration for it.</p>\n<h3>Half-evles and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>Two dragonmarks appear among half-elf families: the <em>Mark of Detection </em>is found in House Medani and the <em>Mark of Storm </em>in House Lyrandar. Both houses were established families among the Khoravar by the time their dragonmarks appeared, and they remain pillars of the Khoravar's diverse culture. The Khoravar ideal of building bridges supports the work of both houses.</p>\n<p>With the <em>Mark of Storm</em>, House Lyrandar operates sailing ships and flying vessels, as well as bringing rain to farmlands. House Medani uses the <em>Mark of Detection</em> to offer services of personal protection.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Heritage:</strong> Half-elves may retain the grace of their elven parent or the adaptability of their human ancestry. A half-elf may either start with a free @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice} Edge of his choice <em>or </em>a d6 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} instead of a d4 (which also increases his @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} maximum to d12+1).</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Half-elves start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Languages]{Elvish}.</li>\n<li><strong>Low-Light Vision:</strong> Half-elves have the eyes of their elven ancestors and their eyes amplify light like a cat's, allowing them to see in the dark. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Skilled:</strong> Sharing the ingenuity of their human relatives as well as having slightly longer life spans, half-elves start with a d4 in any skill based on their experiences, education, training, or culture. If the chosen skill is a core skill, skill), it starts at d6 and the skill's maximum increases to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/half-elf.webp\" alt=\"Dragonmarked khorvar\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/half-elf.webp","_id":"V5WarO1p3xfmYZ6n"}
{"name":"Halfling","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.HFDSzKgJIDSLuYy7"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Halfling</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The halflings of Eberron originate from eastern Khorvaire, and many nomadic tribes of halflings still travel the Talenta Plains. The appearance of dragonmarks among the halflings spurred their slow migration across Khorvaire, spreading their services of healing and hospitality along with the migration of the earliest humans across the continent. Now they are found in every part of Khorvaire, putting their distinctive talents to use.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Talenta Halflings</h3>\n<p>The halflings who migrated across Khorvaire in the company of humans ended up looking very human in dress, manners, and customs. Their cousins who remain in the Talenta Plains could hardly appear more different. In their homeland, halflings are nomads who ride domesticated dinosaurs across the wide plains. Those few Talenta halflings who journey across Khorvaire are visibly out of place, both attracting curious stares and expressing plenty of curiosity of their own about the strange ways of Khorvaire's cities and towns.</p>\n<p>As you make a Talenta halfling character, give some thought to why your character left the open plains. Perhaps you served as a mercenary scout in the Last War, and you've remained with the comrades you met in the conflict. Maybe your tribe was wiped out by a foreign enemy, spurring you to travel the wider world in search of information and revenge. You might be guided by the spirits, who send you whispers and visions that lead you on your adventures. You could be an official envoy of your tribe seeking allies in the world, or simply sent to learn more about the lands beyond the plains.</p>\n<p>Also, consider your relationship to the dinosaurs that play a central role in the life of the Talenta halfiings. You might flavor your spells and class features as dinosaur-related: you could have a clawfoot companion, take on a fastieth form, name your combat styles and maneuvers after dinosaur attacks, or take inspiration from a glidewing (pteranodon) totem spirit. Or you could simply wear a dinosaur mask (as many Talenta halflings do), adorn yourself with claws and teeth from past dinosaur companions, or adopt dinosaur&mdash;like mannerisms. Wherever you travel, your connection to the dinosaurs ofyour home remains strong.</p>\n<p>Finally, it can be helpful to decide on a couple of behavioral quirks that reflect your culture. The Halfling Quirks table can provide some inspiration.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Halflings of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>Quick and charming, many halflings put their natural talents to use as bards, barristers, merchants, and politicians throughout Khorvaire. Of course, these same talents prove equally useful for burglars, grifters, and other criminals.</p>\n<p>Of particular note is the halfling-run criminal enterprise of the Boromar Clan, the most powerful crime syndicate in Breland. The Boromars are based in Sham, but their influence reaches across the nation and even to the distant city of Stormreach. If you decide to play a halfling rogue, or a character with a criminal or charlatan background, consider (with your DM) whether you have a connection to the Boromar Clan. You could be a freelance operative who occasionally gets jobs from a Boromar underboss. You might have a cousin in the syndicate, who occasionally pulls you in to criminal affairs. Or you could even be the reluctant heir of a Boromar leader; perhaps you've gone on the run rather than take your appointed place in the criminal empire, but your past may yet catch up with you. You could also be the point ofcontact who has made the Boromar Clan your party's group patron.</p>\n<h3>Halflings and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>Two dragonmarks appear among the halflings of Khorvaire, the Mark of Healing in House Jorasco and House Ghallanda's Mark of Hospitality. Both marks are ancient, first manifesting among the halflings about the same time that the elves of Aerenal received their first marks&mdash;centuries before the arrival of humans on Khorvaire. Sometimes halflings of House Ghallanda joke that their mark prepared them for the arrival of humans by allowing them to make their new guests comfortable in Khorvaire. There's actually some truth in the humor: the services provided by both halfling houses helped enable the spread of humanity across the continent.</p>\n<p>With its powers related to food and shelter, the Mark of Hospitality was a boon to the early halfling nomads, but now it allows House Ghallanda to run the best inns, hostels, and taverns in the land. Similarly, the Mark of Healing has always been a boon to both nomads and settlers facing dangerous wilds, and HouseJorasco still employs both magical and mundane healing techniques to tend to the well-being of patients across Khorvaire.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Diminutive:</strong> Halfling's average only about four feet tall, reducing their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Halflings start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Halfling}.</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced Pace:</strong> Halflings have short legs compared to human-sized races. Decrease their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} by 1 and their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running die} one die type.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Luck:&nbsp;</strong>Halflings draw one additional @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} per game session. The halfling may freely share their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{bennies} with any other character he can communicate with.</li>\n<li><strong>Spirited: </strong>Halflings are generally optimistic beings. They start with a d6 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/halfling.webp\" alt=\"Talenta Halfling Rider\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/halfling.webp","_id":"VusJttWwYlQ8DNX2"}
{"name":"Hobgoblin","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Xml542xziJ7D56S8"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Hobgoblin</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The goblinoid species-goblins, hobgoblins, and bugbears&mdash;were once the dominant civilization in Khorvaire, with the goblinoid Empire of Dhakaan ruling the continent for thousands of years. It was crippled by a long conflict with the daelkyr and their aberrant armies; even though the daelkyr were defeated, the seeds of madness took root in the empire and tore it apart. Today there are four primary goblinoid cultures in Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>Among the&nbsp;<em>dar</em> or goblin people, hobgoblins are known as&nbsp;<em>ghaal'dar</em> or \"mighty people\". Hobgoblins are the most organized and intelligent of the goblinoid species, often holding the positions of power and organization.</p>\n<h3>The Ghaal'dar</h3>\n<p>The Ghaal'dar tribes arose from the remnants of the Dhakaani Empire. Hobgoblins are the leaders of the Ghaal'dar, enforcing their will on their goblin and bugbear peers. The history of the Ghaal'dar is filled with strife; when they weren't fighting Galifar or Zilargo, the tribes usually turned on one another. This came to an end with the Last War. House Deneith hired Ghaal'dar mercenaries, and this gave focus to the divided tribes. A brilliant hobgoblin, Haruuc, united the Ghaal'dar, and under his leadership they seized control of what is now Darguun. The aging Lhesh Haruuc remains as the ruler of Darguun, and many fear that his death could throw the region into chaos.</p>\n<p>As a Ghaal'dar goblinoid, you hold your place through cunning and strength. You may have been a former mercenary now seeking adventure. You could be working as an emissary for one of the Ghaal'dar tribes or even Lhesh Haruuc himself. Or you could have been driven from your tribe by the actions of a rival; perhaps you're seeking allies to reclaim your birthright.</p>\n<h3>The Heirs of Dhakaan</h3>\n<p>Though the Dhakaani Empire defeated the alien daelkyr, the war left seeds ofcorruption strewn throughout the empire. As Dhakaan began to fall, a number of generals and governors gathered their forces and retreated into shelters deep within the earth, determined to preserve their civilization until the Empire could finally be restored. After thousands of years, their descendants have finally emerged, competing among themselves to determine which leader deserves the imperial crown. Once this is settled, they will turn to the conquest of Darguun and Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>The Dhakaani are far fewer in number than the Ghaal'dar; they had to carefully limit their population in the underground vaults they've dwelled in for the past age. However, they have held onto the martial discipline and techniques that allowed their ancestors to dominate the continent. Their weaponsmiths are superior even to the artificers of House Cannith, and they are experts in the working of adamantine and other exotic metals. Anyone who presumes to look down upon goblinoids should be surprised by the skills of the Dhakaani.</p>\n<p>The Heirs of Dhakaan are an agnostic society and don't have clerics, paladins, or druids. Their focus is on martial excellence, and their spiritual leaders are bards, who tell tales of past glory. Among the Dhakaan, goblinoids work together. Hobgoblins are the strategists and commanders, typically having the skills of fighters, bards, or rangers. Bugbears cultivate a focused battle rage and are typically barbarians. Goblins are largely artisans and laborers, but exceptional goblins join the khesh'dar (\"silent folk\"), learning the skills of rogues, monks, or rangers. The khesh'dar spread agents across the Five Nations, and one can never know when a city goblin might turn out to be an assassin.</p>\n<p>As an adventurer from a Dhakaani clan, consider why are you working with the other player characters? Are you a scout gathering information? Are you searching for allies to defeat a rival clan, or to support your own unlikely bid for the Imperial throne? Are you an exile? If so, do you hope to regain your position, or have you abandoned your ties to the Dhakaani?</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Hobgoblins start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin}<span style=\"color: #191813;\">.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision: </strong>Hobgoblin eyes have become accustomed to the darkness in Khyber. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim or Dark illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Martial Training:</strong> Hobgoblin are trained in war as soon as they can hold a weapon in their hand. They start with a d4 in one skill of their choice from <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Battle]{Battle}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}</em>, or <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}</em>. If the skill is a core skill this will increase the skill's maximum to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Warrior Trained: </strong>Hobgoblins are born and bred as warriors and leaders. Hobgoblins begin play with one free Combat or Leadership @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Edges]{Edge}.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/hobgoblin.webp\" alt=\"Proud hobogoblin warrior.\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/hobgoblin.webp","_id":"W2jC1j3DJRf6zluC"}
{"name":"Arcane Background (Artificer)","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_e33lugmfz55","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Artificer)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Arcane Background (Artificer)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Novice}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts} d8+, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Artifice]{Artifice}&nbsp;d4+</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill: </strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Artifice]{Artifice} (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Smarts})</li>\n<li><strong>Artifice:</strong>&nbsp;Mad scientists may take Edges that require Arcane Background (Weird Science).</li>\n<li><strong>Tools:&nbsp;</strong>Artificers must carry their \"tools\" on their person to activate their powers.</li>\n<li><strong>Malfunction:&nbsp;</strong>When an artificer rolls a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Artifice]{Artifice} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Malfunction Table]{Malfunction Table} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers:</strong> 3</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bind Entity]{Bind Entity}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bridge]{Bridge}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Creation]{Creation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal]{Detect/Conceal}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dimensional Space]{Dimensional Space}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Form]{Elemental Form}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.False Health]{False Health}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Jet]{Jet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Elemental]{Summon Elemental}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Whirlwind]{Whirlwind}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Playing an Artificer</h2>\n<p>In Eberron, magic is almost technology. Spellcasters specialize in certain forms of that technology, while artificers tinker with its fundamental workings. Artificers understand magic on a different level from spellcasters, and do not cast spells as wizards and clerics do. They have an amazing facility with magic items and constructs, and in many ways, they keep the magical world of Eberron running.</p>\n<p>Masters of unlocking magic in everyday objects, artificers are supreme inventors. They see magic as a complex system waiting to be decoded and controlled. Artificers use tools to channel arcane power, crafting magical objects. To cast a spell, an artificer could use alchemist's supplies to create a potent elixir, calligrapher's supplies to inscribe a sigil of power on an ally's armor, or tinker's tools to craft a temporary charm. The magic of artificers is tied to their tools and their talents.</p>\n<h3>ARCANE SCIENCE</h3>\n<p>In the world of Eberron, arcane magic has been harnessed as a form of science and deployed throughout society. Artificers reflect this development. Their knowledge of magical devices, and their ability to infuse mundane items with magic, allows Eberron's most miraculous projects to continue.</p>\n<p>During the Last War, artificers were marshaled on a massive scale. Many lives were saved because of the inventions of brave artificers, but countless lives were also lost because of the mass destruction unleashed by their creations.</p>\n<h3>SEEKERS OF NEW LORE</h3>\n<p>Nothing excites an artificer quite like uncovering a new metal or discovering a source of elemental energy. In artificer circles, new inventions and strange discoveries create the most excitement. Artificers who wish to make their mark must innovate, creating something fresh, rather than iterating on familiar designs.</p>\n<p>This drive for novelty pushes artificers to become adventurers. Eberron's main travel routes and populated regions have long since been explored. Thus, artificers seek the frontiers of civilization in hopes of making the next great discovery in arcane research.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>Artificers craft, invent, and tinker with their inventions. All your powers are produced by inventions that are crafted using various tools. When creating an artificer, pick at least one kind of tool set that the artificer works with; @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Alchemist Supplies]{alchemist supplies} for potions and ungents, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Tinker's Tools]{tinker's tools} for general tinkering, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Warforged Repair Kit]{warforged repair kit} if they work strictly with warforged, or another artisan tool kit that makes sense.</p>\n<p>In general, it's assumed an artificer is constantly working and tinker on their inventions during downtime. Perhaps before bed, in the morning, or during meals. It should be assumed the inventor takes at least an hour a day preparing items that might be used. If the artificer can't perform this tinkering, or does not have their tools, she can't use her powers.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>As an artificer, you use tools when you cast your spells. When describing your spellcasting, think about how you're using a tool to perform the spell effect. If you cast <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> using @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Alchemist Supplies]{alchemist supplies}, you could be quickly producing a salve. If you cast it using @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Tinker's Tools]{tinker's tools}, you might have a miniature mechanical spider that binds wounds. When you cast <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}</em> with a poison effect, you could fling foul chemicals or use a wand that spits venom.</p>\n<p>Artificers take pride in their custom inventions, often giving them creative names to differentiate them from other artificers. Such as \"Elenna's Miraculous Healing Ungent\" or \"Mending Spider\". You should make sure to do the same for your powers.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"WkAQaYluuHPWNKAx"}
