{"name":"Skills","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_jtibz2gzdj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Skills</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.More Skill Points]{More Skill Points} Setting Rule is in effect, therefore all characters start with 15 points to buy skills during character creation. A skill that&rsquo;s below the linked attribute (noted in parentheses beside the skill name) is cheaper to increase than one that&rsquo;s at or above it. See <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Character Creation Summary]{Character Creation}</strong> and <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Advancement}.</strong></p>\n<p>Core skills are marked with a <span class=\"red-text\">red star</span>, and start at d4 for@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{player characters}.</p>\n<p>Characters can attempt skills they don&rsquo;t have but it&rsquo;s more difficult. See<strong> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Unskilled Attempts}</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Skill changes in Savage Eberron from Savage Worlds</h2>\n<p>The following skills from <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> are not available in <cite>Savage Eberron.</cite></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Academics</span> has been renamed to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Lore]{Lore}</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Driving</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Electronics</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Hacking</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Occult</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Piloting</span>&nbsp;has been updated to be used with elemental bound vehicles.</li>\n<li><span class=\"red-text\">Repair</span> has been updated to be used with artifice and warforged.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<figure class=\"figure table-figure\">\n<figcaption class=\"figure-heading\">Skill Summaries</figcaption>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Skills</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Animal Handling]{Animal Handling} (Spirit):</span> Skill with handling and training animals.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcan]{Arcana} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge about the spells, artifacts, magical traditions, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (Agility):</span> Overall athletic coordination and ability. Climbing, jumping, balancing, wrestling, skiing, swimming, throwing, or catching.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Battle]{Battle} (Smarts):</span> Strategy, tactics, and understanding military operations. A key skill in Mass Battles.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Boating]{Boating} (Agility):</span> Ability to sail or pilot a boat, ship, or other watercraft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} (Smarts):</span> General knowledge of a character&rsquo;s world.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Cosmology]{Cosmology} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of the planes, their properties, inhabitants, and manifest zones.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Crafting]{Crafting} (Smarts):</span> The ability to control, steer, and operate ground vehicles.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} (Agility):</span> Skill in armed and unarmed combat.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Gambling]{Gambling} (Smarts):</span> Skill and familiarity with games of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Healing]{Healing} (Smarts):</span> The ability to treat and heal Wounds and diseases, and decipher forensic evidence.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Herbalism] (Smarts):</span> The specialist knowledge of plants and herbs, and how to extract remedies from them.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} (Spirit):</span> A character&rsquo;s ability to threaten others into doing what she wants.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge and fluency in a particular language.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Lore]{Lore} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of History, Ages, Legends, literature, song, poetry, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} (Smarts):</span> General awareness and perception.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} (Spirit):</span> Singing, dancing, acting, or other forms of public expression.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} (Spirit):</span> The ability to convince others to do what you want.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting]{Piloting} (Agility):</span> Skill with maneuvering elemental bound vehicles.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Religion]{Religion} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge about religions, rites, traditions and symbols.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} (Smarts):</span> The ability to fix mechanical gadgets, vehicles and warforged.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Research]{Research} (Smarts):</span> Finding written information from various sources.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Riding]{Riding} (Agility):</span> A character&rsquo;s skill in mounting, controlling, and riding a tamed beast.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Science]{Science} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of scientific fields such as biology, chemistry, geology, engineering, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} (Agility):</span> Precision with any type of ranged weapon.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold core-skill\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} (Agility):</span> The ability to sneak and hide.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Survival]{Survival} (Smarts):</span> How to find food, water, or shelter, and tracking.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} (Smarts):</span> Insulting or belittling another. Almost always done as a Test.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Traditions]{Traditions} (Smarts):</span> Knowledge of court ettiquette and courtesies.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} (Agility):</span> Sleight of hand, pickpocketing, lockpicking, and other typically shady feats.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Skills for Arcane Backgrounds</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Artifice]{Artifice} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artifice)]{Arcane Background (Artifice)}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Dragonmark Focus]{Dragonmark Focus} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Dragonmark)]{Arcane Background (Dragonmark)}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Druidism]{Druidism} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Druidism)]{Arcane Background (Druidism)}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Faith]{Faith} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Background (Miracles)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Focus]{Focus} (Spirit):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Background (Gifted)]{Arcane Background (Gifted)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Arcane Background (Psionics)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Song Magic]{Song Magic} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Song Magic)]{Arcane Background (Song Magic)}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Background (Magic)]{Arcane Background (Magic)}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Wand Magic]{Wand Magic} (Smarts):</span> The arcane skill for&nbsp;@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Wandslinger)]{Arcane Background (Wandslinger)}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"cjFOv7huT4LzC1Wn"}
{"name":"Ranger","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.au2sH7tVPH13NkjL"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>The classic image of the ranger is a warden of the wilds, a cunning skirmisher with a touch of druidic magic, but the ranger can fill many roles. A typical ranger is perceptive and stealthy, familiar with the wilds and a subject matter expert on the habits and tactics of a variety of Enemies.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Animal Handling, Fighting, Healing, Notice, Riding, Shooting, Stealth, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Ambidextrous, Fleet-Footed, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Dead Shot, Extraction, Improved Extraction, Favored Foe, Marksman, Two-Fisted</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Explorer, Monster Hunter, Woodsman</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Beast Bond, Beast Master, Healer</p>","_id":"cwwaFu2hLD2oCI96"}
{"name":"Diplomat","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.loVCK5EwenityQtq"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Khorvaire is a miasma of different races and cultures, and keeping the peace of the Last War is a full time job. As well as trying to maintain the status quo, many diplomats seek to better the options for their nations with the Dragonmark Houses.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Femme Fatale/Ladykiller</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Reliable, Work the Room</p>","_id":"cxwvFS2YtZVkZuY1"}
{"name":"Languages","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_jtibz2gzdj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Languages</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>In Eberron, languages reflect culture and geography; a dwarf raised in Breland might not know Dwarvish, but a halfling raised in the Mror Holds might. The historical development of languages and cultures also explains the scripts used to write various languages. For example, the Orc language is written using the Goblin script, because the orcs of Khorvaire learned writing from the goblins. Common is the language of the Five Nations and the language of trade in Khorvaire, known by most of its people. Goblin was the trade language of the goblin empire of Dhakaan and survives as the primary language in Darguun, Droaam, and the Shadow Marches. Goblin displaced the Orc language; the people of the Shadow Marches typically speak Goblin, and Orc is an exotic language. Members of all races in Xen'drik speak Giant and use it as their trade language. Infernal is the common tongue of all fiends, while Celestial is \"the tongue of Siberys.\"</p>\n<h3>Welcome to Eberron</h3>\n<p>With the DM's approval, you can exchange a language granted by your race for a different language from the Standard Languages of Eberron table. Ifyour halfling was raised in the Mror Holds, you might replace Halfling with Dwarvish to reflect that background. The DM may change the languages assigned to a monster or NPC. An ogre from Droaam likely speaks Goblin instead of Giant.</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Standard Languages</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Language</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Typical Speakers</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Script</th>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Common</td>\n<td>Citizens of Khorvaire</td>\n<td>Common</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dwarven</td>\n<td>Mror Holds</td>\n<td>Dwarvish</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Elven</td>\n<td>Aerenal, Valenar</td>\n<td>Sylvan</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\n<td>Goblin</td>\n<td>Darguun, Droaam, Shadow Marches, monsters of Khorvaire</td>\n<td>Goblin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gnomish</td>\n<td>Zilargo</td>\n<td>Dwarvish</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Halfling</td>\n<td>Talenta Plains</td>\n<td>Goblin</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Exotic Languages</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Language</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Typical Speakers</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Script</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Daelkyr</td>\n<td>Daelkyr, mind flayers, other aberrations, and creatures of Xoriat</td>\n<td>Daelkyr</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Draconic</td>\n<td>Kobolds, lizardfolk, troglodytes, dragons, arcane uses</td>\n<td>Draconic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Druidic</td>\n<td>Druids, Eldeen Reaches</td>\n<td>Draconic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Giant</td>\n<td>Native inhabitants of Xen'drik</td>\n<td>Giant</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Orc</td>\n<td>Isolated orc tribes</td>\n<td>Goblin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Riedran</td>\n<td>People of Sarlona</td>\n<td>Common</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sahuagin</td>\n<td>Sahuagin, sailors</td>\n<td>Sahuagin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Khyber's Tongue</td>\n<td>Denizens of Khyber, symbionts</td>\n<td>Daelkyr</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Planar Languages</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Language</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Typical Speakers</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Script</th>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Celestial</td>\n<td>Celestials, Archons of Shavarath, couatl, shulassukar</td>\n<td>Celestial</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Infernal</td>\n<td>Beings of Shavarath, Lords of Dust, tieflings</td>\n<td>Infernal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Irial</td>\n<td>Deathless, energy beings of Irian</td>\n<td>Celestial</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Quori</td>\n<td>Inspired, kalashtar, quori</td>\n<td>Quori</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Primordial</td>\n<td>Elementals</td>\n<td>Primordial</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sylvan</td>\n<td>Dryads, eladrin, fey of Thelanis and woodland beings</td>\n<td>Sylvan</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"dWdIb9YRmcA8jQxs"}
{"name":"Cleric","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.z8YQ22r7SzqkZWpt"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>It’s important to understand that in Eberron, not all priests can wield divine energies. A priest provides spiritual guidance to a community and congregation and they don’t need magic to do this. A cleric is a full-fledged divine champion, and someone who possesses such a powerful connection wouldn’t waste that power on sermons and everyday services. People of faith assume that such power has a purpose.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Faith, Fighting, Healing, Religion</p>\n<p><strong>Hindrance: </strong>Chain of Command, Vow</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Miracles), Attractive, Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Any combat edge for a warrior cleric</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Command, Fantaticism, Inspire</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Holy/Unholy Warrior</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Holy Adept</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Strong Willed, Iron Will, Work the Room</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Champion</p>","_id":"dm5rUlLFjvChp1vz"}
{"name":"Fatiguing","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_53szy0z05dw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.3. Power Modifiers","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core\">\n<h3>Fatiguing</h3>\n<p>Powers that drain or tax an opponent can cause @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. This modifier may be attached to any @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Powers]{power} that can cause damage or is resisted by the target for an additional &minus;2 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier}. If she&rsquo;s affected by the power in any way, she also suffers Fatigue. This cannot cause @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitation}, however.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"dxVgdLXW7UaaHiyI"}
{"name":"Hindrances","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_jtibz2gzdj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Hindrances</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Hindrances are character flaws and physical handicaps that occasionally make life a little tougher for your hero.</p>\n<p>Some Hindrances have actual game effects. Other, more subjective &ldquo;roleplaying&rdquo; Hindrances help you understand and roleplay your character. They should occasionally cause her to act in ways that aren&rsquo;t necessarily smart, efficient, or in the best interests of the party or the overall goal. That&rsquo;s what roleplaying games are all about, and the GM should reward you with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies] when your Hindrances cause significant trouble.</p>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"figure table-figure\">\n<figcaption class=\"figure-heading\">Hindrance Summaries</figcaption>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.All Thumbs] (Minor):</span> &ndash;2 to use mechanical or electrical devices.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Anemic]{Anemic} (Minor):</span> &ndash;2 @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} when resisting @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Apprentice/Novice]{Apprentice/Novice} (Minor/Major): </span>Cannot start with higher than a d6 in arcane skill, as Major start with one less power from the Arcane Background.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Arrogant]{Arrogant} (Minor):</span> Likes to dominate his opponent, challenge the most powerful foe in combat.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Bad Eyes]{Bad Eyes} (Minor/Major):</span> &ndash;1 to all Trait rolls dependent on vision, or &ndash;2 as a Major Hindrance. Eyewear negates penalty but have a 50% chance of breaking when the hero suffers trauma.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Bad Luck]{Bad Luck} (Major):</span> The characters starts with one less Benny per session.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Big Mouth]{Big Mouth} (Minor):</span> Unable to keep secrets and constantly gives away private information.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Blind]{Blind} (Major):</span> &ndash;6 to all tasks that require vision (but choice of a free Edge to offset).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Bloodthirsty]{Bloodthirsty} (Major):</span> Never takes prisoners.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Can't Swim]{Can't Swim} (Minor):</span> &ndash;2 to swimming (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}) rolls; Each inch moved in water costs 3&rdquo; of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Cautious]{Cautious} (Minor):</span> The character plans extensively and/or is overly careful.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Chain of Command]{Chain of Command} (Minor/Major):</span> You have to follow orders from a superior, as Major you are expendable.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Clueless]{Clueless} (Major):</span> &ndash;1 to Common Knowledge and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Clumsy]{Clumsy} (Major):</span> &ndash;2 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Code of Honor]{Code of Honor} (Major):</span> The character keeps his word and acts like a gentleman.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Combat Shock]{Combat Shock} (Minor/Major):</span> First round of combat make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fear]{Fear} check, at &ndash;2 for Major Hindrance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Curious]{Curious} (Major):</span> The character wants to know about everything.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Death Wish]{Death Wish} (Minor):</span> The hero wants to die after or while completing some epic task.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Delusional]{Delusional} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual believes something strange that causes him occasional or frequent trouble.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Dependant]{Dependant} (Minor):</span> The hero has a dependant they must care for.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Deserter]{Deserter} (Minor/Major):</span> The adventurer was a deserter from the Last War.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Doubting Thomas]{Doubting Thomas} (Minor):</span> The character doesn&rsquo;t believe in the supernatural, often exposing him to unnecessary risks.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Driven]{Driven} (Minor/Major):</span> The hero&rsquo;s actions are driven by some important goal or belief.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Elderly]{Elderly} (Major):</span> &ndash;1 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}, running, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility, Strength, and Vigor}. Hero gets 5 extra skill points.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} (Minor/Major):</span> The character has a recurring nemesis.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Fanatic]{Fanatic} (Major):</span> The hero fanatically believes in his country, monarch, or religion.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Greedy]{Greedy} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual is obsessed with wealth and material possessions.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Habit]{Habit} (Minor/Major):</span> Addicted to something, suffers Fatigue if deprived.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Hard of Hearing]{Hard of Hearing} (Minor/Major):</span> &ndash;4 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} sounds; automatic failure if completely deaf.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Heavy Sleeper]{Heavy Sleeper} (Major):</span> &ndash;4 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to wake up. &ndash;4 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} to stay awake.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Heroic]{Heroic} (Major):</span> The character always helps those in need.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} (Minor):</span> Draw two @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Cards} and take the lowest (except Jokers, which may be kept).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Illiterate]{Illiterate} (Minor):</span> The character cannot read or write.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Impulsive]{Impulsive} (Major):</span> The hero leaps before he looks.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Jealous]{Jealous} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual covets what others have.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Lying Eyes]{Lying Eyes} (Minor):</span> &ndash;1 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Gambling]{Gambling}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls when lying.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Loyal]{Loyal} (Minor):</span> The hero is loyal to his friends and allies.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Mean]{Mean} (Minor):</span> &ndash;1 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Mild Mannered]{Mild Mannered} (Minor):</span> &ndash;2 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Mute]{Mute} (Major):</span> The hero cannot speak.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Night Terrors]{Night Terrors} (Minor):</span> &ndash;1 penalty to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Spirit} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Nightmares]{Nightmares} (Minor):</span> Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} check every morning or suffer @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Obese]{Obese} (Minor):</span> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} +1, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} &ndash;1 and running die of d4. Treat Strength as one die type lower for Min Str.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Obligation]{Obligation} (Minor/Major):</span> The character has a weekly obligation of 20 (Minor) to 40 (Major) hours.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.One Arm]{One Arm} (Major):</span> &ndash;4 to tasks (such as @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}) that require two hands.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.One Eye]{One Eye} (Major):</span> &ndash;2 to actions at 5&Prime; (10 yards) or more distance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Outsider]{Outsider} (Minor/Major):</span> The character doesn&rsquo;t fit in to the local environment and subtracts 2 from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls. As a Major Hindrance she has no legal rights or other serious consequences.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Overconfident]{Overconfident} (Major):</span> The hero believes she can do anything.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Pacifist]{Pacifist} (Minor/Major):</span> Fights only in self-defense as a Minor Hindrance, won&rsquo;t fight at all as Major.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Phobia]{Phobia} (Minor/Major):</span> The character is afraid of something, and subtracts &ndash;1/&ndash;2 from all Trait rolls in its presence.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Poverty]{Poverty} (Minor):</span> Half starting funds and the character is always broke.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Quirk]{Quirk} (Minor):</span> The individual has some minor but persistent foible that often annoys others.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Ruthless]{Ruthless} (Minor/Major):</span> The character does what it takes to get her way.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Secret]{Secret} (Minor/Major):</span> The hero has a dark secret of some kind.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Screamer]{Screamer} (Minor):</span> When the hero fails @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fear]{Fear} test they scream at top of their lungs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Shamed]{Shamed} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual is haunted by some tragic event from her past.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Slow]{Slow} (Minor/Major):</span> Pace &ndash;1, reduce running die one step. As Major, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace} &ndash;2, &ndash;2 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} and rolls to resist @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}. Neither may take the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Fleet-Footed]{Fleet-Footed} Edge.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Small]{Small} (Minor):</span> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} and Toughness are reduced by 1. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} cannot be reduced below &ndash;1.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Stubborn]{Stubborn} (Minor):</span> The character wants his way and rarely admits his mistakes.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Suspicious]{Suspicious} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual is paranoid. As a Major Hindrance, allies subtract 2 when rolling to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Support]{Support} him.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Thin Skinned]{Thin Skinned} (Minor/Major):</span> The character is particularly susceptible to personal attacks. As a Minor Hindrance, he subtracts two when resisting Taunt attacks. As a Major, he subtracts four.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Tongue-Tied]{Tongue-Tied} (Major):</span> The character often misspeaks or can&rsquo;t get her words out. &ndash;1 to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Trouble Magnet]{Trouble Magnet} (Minor/Major):</span> The adventurer always seems to attract the worst kind of trouble.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Ugly]{Ugly} (Minor/Major):</span> The character is physically unattractive and subtracts 1 or 2 from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Vengeful]{Vengeful} (Minor/Major):</span> The adventurer seeks payback for slights against her. As a Major Hindrance, she&rsquo;ll cause physical harm to get it.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Victim]{Victim} (Minor/Major):</span> The adventure is always the target of \"random\" attacks. Major hindrance causes &ndash;1 to all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak rolls}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Vow]{Vow} (Minor/Major):</span> The individual has pledged himself to some cause.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Wanted]{Wanted} (Minor/Major):</span> The character is wanted by the authorities.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Yellow]{Yellow} (Major):</span> &ndash;2 to Fear checks and resisting @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"lead-bold\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Young]{Young} (Minor/Major):</span> Minor has 4 attribute points and 10 skill points, extra @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} per session. Major has 3 attribute points, 10 skill points, and two extra Bennies per session.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</figure>\n<img class=\"figure table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/atmosphere/camp.webp\" alt=\"Heavy sleepers at an adventuring camp.\" /></div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"egQcd7qXf6Edf9NE"}
{"name":"Add Armor Piercing","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_53szy0z05dw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.3. Power Modifiers","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core\">\n<h3>Add Armor Piercing</h3>\n<p>The attack is focused to defeat armor or seeks out a foe&rsquo;s exposed areas. For each &minus;1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier}, the power gains @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{AP 2}, to a max&shy;imum of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{AP 6}.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"fTuyGb1YCtVSQ5ds"}
{"name":"Magewright","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.owEB6QK3kUGdi03l"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Magewrights highly skilled and focused on a few certain spells, which they use to craft specific magical technology. They are most frequently found in cities and large towns, where they are about as common as adepts.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Crafting, Dragonmark Focus, Lore, Magecraft, Repair, Research, Science</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Making or Magecraft)</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Artificer, Adept Artificer, Master Artificer, Attune Arcane Weapon, Enchant, Improved Enchant, Expert Artificer, Finely Tuned, Imbue Item, Tinkerer</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Jack-of-all-Trades, Mr. Fix It</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Scavenger</p>","_id":"g4vyhJuLyRpDqwB7"}
{"name":"Traps","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_v2dfoof50lp","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"header\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p>Traps</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n<p>Draw two cards from the Action Deck whenever you need a trap on the fly. These tell you everything you need to know about its concealment, complexity, type, and lethality. Very occasionally you'll need to draw a third card, but the rules below tell you when to do this.</p>\n<p>The GM should add suitable flavor to these draws based on the trap type. For instance, a \"blade trap\" could be a scything blade slicing from the wall at knee height or a spear which thrusts out from a concealed hole. A Spade result on the trap might indicate multiple blades, hence the high Fighting die and increased damage. A portcullis of the Club suit might be heavily corroded or made of wood, whereas a Spade indicates extremely tough and well-made bars.</p>\n<h3>First Card</h3>\n<p>The first card determines how difficult the trap is to detect and disarm. This is shown on the <strong>Trap Difficulty Table</strong> below as modifiers to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery] rolls.</p>\n<p>Note that <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{glyph}</em> traps cannot be disarmed by mundane means (and so ignore the suit), but they can be&nbsp;<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispelled} </em>and negated. Use the suit entry of the second card on the Trap Type table below to determine the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill} die for this purpose.</p>\n<p><strong>Detecting: </strong>Detecting a trap requires a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Unless a character has @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-edges.Danger Sense], searching for traps requires an action. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{running} hero rolls at &ndash;2. A single roll is made in a round, regardless of how far the hero moves. With success, he detects the first trap adjacent to him. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise} locates a second trap within line of sight, if such exists. The hero may halt his movement if he spots a trap (advisable if it's right in front of him).</p>\n<p><strong>Disarming: </strong>Disarming a detected trap requires a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery] roll and takes a complete round (no other actions possible, including movement). On a critical failure, the trap activates and automatically affects the unfortunate hero.</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Trap Difficulty Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Value</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Detect</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Suit</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Disarm</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Joker</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>Joker</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2&ndash;4</td>\n<td>+1</td>\n<td>Club</td>\n<td>+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5&ndash;10</td>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>Diamond</td>\n<td>0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jack&ndash;Queen</td>\n<td>&ndash;1</td>\n<td>Heart</td>\n<td>&ndash;1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>King&ndash;Ace</td>\n<td>&ndash;2</td>\n<td>Spade</td>\n<td>&ndash;2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<br />\n<h3>Second Card</h3>\n<p>The second card determines the exact type of trap encountered. This is detailed on the <strong>Trap Type Table</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Wild Die: </strong>On a Joker the trap is exceptionally lethal and has a Wild Die. Draw a third card to determine the trap type. The suit of the new card indicates the Wild Die, as well as other details. Traps with a Wild Die apply it to rolls to all Trait rolls, when applicable.</p>\n<p><strong>Area: </strong>Traps usually affect a 1\" square on the battle grid. Ranged attacks use the standard range brackets for the type of missile launched. Whatever projectile is launched, range is calculated as normal. The distance listed for pits is their depth.&nbsp;<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph} </em>traps affect an area or operate at range as per the spell description and the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill} die.</p>\n<p><strong>Duration: </strong>Traps are generally one-shot devices. Once activated, they must be reset in order to work again. Portcullises remain in place until lifted up.</p>\n<p><strong>Initiative:</strong> Most traps activate with little warning to the unfortunate victim. Outside of combat use the rules for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Surprise]. In combat, traps being on Hold and roll to interrupt. Traps have @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} d10 for this purpose. A trap also has @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.The Drop]{the Drop} where applicable. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to avoid @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Surprise] and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} rolls to avoid interruption use the same modifier as for Detecting traps (see above).</p>\n<p><strong>Attacks: </strong>Traps which make attack rolls cannot use any combat maneuvers&mdash;they simply roll their attack die.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes: </strong>The following short codes are used on the table. Arcane = @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane skill}. Used when a spell activates, requires an attribute die value for any reason, and to resist dispel attempts. Fight = @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting] skill. Sh = @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Shooting] skill (range and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} modifiers apply). @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength}&ndash;X = penalty to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} roll to lift obstacle. XdY = number and type of damage dice. #X = number of attacks a trap makes against a single victim or can split among multiple victims (GM's call based on placement). Traps which use @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Shooting] do not suffer penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}.</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Trap Type Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Value</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Clubs</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Diamonds</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Hearts</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Spades</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Joker*</td>\n<td>&ndash;</td>\n<td>d4 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d6 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d8 Wild Die</td>\n<td>d10 Wild Die</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Portcullis**</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> &ndash;1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> &ndash;2</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> &ndash;4</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Strength</a> &ndash;6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3&ndash;4</td>\n<td>Pit Trap***</td>\n<td>10', 1d6</td>\n<td>20', 2d6</td>\n<td>30', 3d6</td>\n<td>40', 4d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Spiked Pit</td>\n<td>10', 1d6+2</td>\n<td>20', 2d6+4</td>\n<td>30', 3d6+6</td>\n<td>40', 4d6+8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6&ndash;8</td>\n<td>Projectile</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d6, 2d6, #1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d8, 2d6, #1</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d10, 2d6, #3</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\"> Sh</a> d12, 2d6, #4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9&ndash;10</td>\n<td>Blade</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d6, 2d6</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d8, 2d8</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d10, 2d10</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\"> Fight</a> d12, 2d12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jack</td>\n<td>Poisoned</td>\n<td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Projectile of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1&ndash;3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\"> Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4&ndash;7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8&ndash;10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Wound</a>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Queen</td>\n<td>Poisoned</td>\n<td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Blade of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\"> Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1&ndash;3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\"> Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4&ndash;7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8&ndash;10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\"> Wound</a>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>King</td>\n<td>Falling Block</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>2d8</td>\n<td>3d6</td>\n<td>3d8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ace</td>\n<td><em><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers\" data-id=\"BTDWriPb4tGpCIQm\"> Glyph</a>****</em></td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d6</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d8</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d10</td>\n<td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\"> Arcane</a> d12</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>* Draw a third card to determine Wild Die and trap type. A second Joker indicates the trap is faulty and does not work.</p>\n<p>** Portcullis traps either have a single gate (usually to block the way the party has come and so force them forward) or drop two gates (one ahead and one behind the intruders to trap them in a small area). Due to the confines of most corridors or doorways, a maximum of two people can combine their Strength in a Cooperative roll to lift a portcullis.</p>\n<p>*** Alternately, a pit may drop the victims into a lower level of the &ldquo;dungeon&rdquo; rather than a small hole, thus separating the party. Another version could be a chute, which drops the victim into a cell or monster&rsquo;s lair on a lower level but without inflicting any damage.</p>\n<p>**** One spell of the GM&rsquo;s choice.</p>\n<section class=\"secret\">\n<h3>TRAP EXAMPLE</h3>\n<p>Aelric Olafsunu is exploring a ruined temple when the GM decides to place a trap in his path. The GM draws two cards. He gets a 3 of Hearts and the King of Diamonds.</p>\n<p>The 3H tells the GM that there is a +1 bonus to the Notice roll to spot the trap (indicated by the 3) and a &ndash;1 modifier to disarm it (indicated by the Hearts). The trap is fairly complex, but not very well disguised. Unfortunately, Aelric isn't looking out for traps and walks straight onto it. The GM decides it is a pressure plate mechanism.</p>\n<p>As this occurs outside of combat, Aelric rolls his Notice to avoid Surprise. He adds +1 from the first card's value, and scores 8. The GM tells Aelric he hears an audible click as his foot hits the floor and deals him an action card. Aelric declares he wants to move clear of the square he is on. Before he can do this, however, the trap tries to interrupt him.</p>\n<p>The trap has a fixed d10 Agility and rolls a 9. Aelric rolls his Agility and gets a lousy 5. Aelric has been hit by a falling lump of masonry (as determined by the King value of the second card). He suffers 2d8 damage (determined by the Diamonds).</p>\n<p>Note that although the trap scored a raise over Aelric's Agility total, this was not an attack roll and so it does not deal +1d6 damage.</p>\n<p>Aelric suffers 11 damage, enough to cause him a wound. He vows to be more careful as he descends deeper into the temple.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"gpBbYTBIQh39uRPC"}
{"name":"Noble","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.zds95QdTAYavucmH"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>The highest levels of nobility are shared among the nations of Khorvaire, but other nobles exist among families of great import or strong political ties.</p>\n<p>When Galifar was founded, the Five Nations all employed forms of medieval feudalism. Nobles governed lands tended by tenant farmers in exchange for providing taxes and military service to the leader of the nation. In many nations, the nobility was also responsible for the administration of justice. Galifar was built on this framework. It was acknowledged that all power and authority flowed from the sovereign, through the princes and princesses that governed the land, and then down through local nobles and administrators. Throughout Galifar, the nobility remained the foundation of the united kingdom. Nobles were responsible for maintaining their territory, including collecting taxes and raising levies for military and national service. Under the Galifar Code of Justice, the nobles didn&rsquo;t administer justice, but it was their duty to maintain the system, appointing justices and maintaining the local courts. As the kingdom expanded and as life became increasingly more complicated, this produced a class of dedicated civil servants and landowners&mdash;initially ennobled viscounts and crown reeves, but ultimately expanding into gentry and merchant classes. But at the start of the Last War, it remained the case that the majority of property was associated with a noble&rsquo;s domain, and that it was the local lord who appointed justices, mayors, and other officials. A crown reeve was responsible to the count, the count to their duke, the duke to the prince, the prince to the king.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Common Knowledge, Intimidation, Persuasion, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Aristocract, Charismatic, House Scion, Rich, Filthy Rich</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections</p>","_id":"gxECvxnAkP6qlajl"}
{"name":"Elf","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L4NqGfd9AVja33DY"},"cf":{"id":"temp_7967rzk60vt","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Elf</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Tens of thousands ofyears ago, the elves of the distant continent of Xen'drik rose up against the giants who ruled over them. This rebellion is the defining event in elf history. As the ancient war progressed, the magebreeders of the giants bound magic into the elves who remained loyal to them, forming the drow-assassins bred to prey on their other kin. Ultimately, the elves fled from Xen'drik and settled the island nation of Aerenal, where they split into two distinct cultures: the introspective Aereni and the warlike Tairnadal. Thus, a war nearly forty thousand years ago established the pattern of how elves live today.</p>\n<p>Neither the Aereni nor the Tairnadal (which include the elves of Valenar) have much interest in human activities, but small numbers of elves have immigrated to Khorvaire over the centuries and have more or less integrated with the cultures of the Five Nations. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-races.aVHntifcJ9GmX4Y1]{drow}, though, are virtually unknown on Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>As a whole, elves are driven by tradition and respect for the past. Where humans value innovation, elves strive to master and perfect the techniques of their ancestors over the course of studies lasting centuries. Elf society has changed little over the last five thousand years, while Khorvaire is constantly evolving. Whatever the origin of your elf character, consider your relationship wit.h the past: Do you value the traditions ofyour ancestors? Or do you fear that your people are too mired in the past, and need to find a way to adapt and move forward?</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 1.125em;\">Elves of the Five Nations</span></h3>\n<p>Throughout history, elves have occasionally migrated to live among the other peoples of Khorvaire. On rare occasions, entire families have relocated (as House Phiarlan did, almost three thousand years ago), but more often wanderers and exiles have come to Khorvaire and made their way there.</p>\n<p>As an elf born and raised in Khorvaire, your character has grown up among the shorter-lived races. You might not be as concerned with history and tradition as the Aereni and Tairnadal; you could even live your life entirely in the moment, with no care for your family or your legacy. Or you could be fascinated by the history and traditions ofyour ancestors and try to relearn the ways your family has forgotten.</p>\n<p>Consider also whether you've outlived human friends and how that might affect you. Did you know the parents or grandparents of another member of your party? Are you trying to repay a debt or fulfill a promise to that long-dead friend, or are you trying to recapture some spark of the friendship you felt years ago? Do you remember a time before the Last War? Did you fight in the war?</p>\n<h3>Elves and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>Mark of Shadow</em> first appeared among the elves of the Phiarlan line, and the house quickly turned the mark's powers of shadow and illusion into an economic dynasty. The suspicion of their kin drove them from Aerenal to Khorvaire, and the house splintered during the Last War, giving rise to House Thuranni. The two houses of shadow control the business of espionage throughout Khorvaire, but they also operate more legitimate ventures related to art and entertainment.</p>\n<p>Phiarlan blood still runs among some of the Aereni elves, and the <em>Mark of Shadow </em>appears once or twice in each elven generation. Elves bearing this mark are always inducted into the elite force of the Cairdal Bladesan espionage agency in the service of Aerenal's Sibling Kings.</p>\n<h3>Aereni and Tairnadal</h3>\n<p>For thousands of years, the island nation of Aerenal has been ruled and protected by the godlike power of the Undying Court, a council of undead high elves. The greatest heroes of the Aereni join the Undying Court after death, joining their heroic ancestors in immortality.</p>\n<p>Tairnadal elves dedicate themselves to the arts of war. The greatest heroes of the Tairnadal's many wars-against giants, dragons, and the champions of Dhakaan&mdash;live on after death, becoming the patron ancestors of the Tairnadal. Upon reaching adulthood, a Tairnadal elf forms a bond with one of these ancestors and strives to follow in the footsteps of this ancestor, living as the patron did. In this way, the champion comes to embody their ancestor, allowing the dead to live on.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Agile:</strong> Elves are graceful and agile. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Agility} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Frail:&nbsp;</strong>Elves are graceful but more frail as other races. They subtact 1 from their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Keen Vision (Elf)]{Keen Vision}:</strong> Elves have exceptionally keen senses. They add +1 to any @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} check.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Elves start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Elvish}.</li>\n<li><strong>Low Light Vision: </strong>Elves eyes amplify light like a cat's, allowing them to see in the dark. They ignore penalties for @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination} (but not Pitch Darkness).</li>\n<li><strong>Trance:&nbsp;</strong>Elves don't need sleep, but they must meditate in a semiconscious state 4 hours every day. As a result elves are immune to sleep like effects.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/races/elf.webp\" alt=\"Group of dragonmarked elves.\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-rules/assets/art/elf.webp","_id":"hn1oMCipYP2AAUOv"}
{"name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000","name":"1.2. Character Concepts","children":["EjxNeGAbkirBgwTg","6xr1RC4aeFj9LP69","wopbuylyl15BnCtB","aOQbfzWZeA0eiWMN","6G4YL27CnASfypoT","BSRf81HtWajoMMTq","IBtAhU4ArkthDtDs","mEEAmdsvWqtD6hAy","dm5rUlLFjvChp1vz","cxwvFS2YtZVkZuY1","8SR0QOFgrFXZsxlJ","5fo4HxU4IdUQo7pv","PPKpygcDlcUp7xrZ","qIiiMLFp1EWvvr3w","kd8opJureBSMcoSR","U9TWWJXzhTLy3RFD","Un0lcuopqqmHAqZY","PYSBtlBkzr3A5sDa","g4vyhJuLyRpDqwB7","rnahacQ4wRnGvOoW","kDyEk332QR4nC4qr","lPUkD9iZnWVoGui1","gxECvxnAkP6qlajl","ljQ8DjaXhuYgnc9y","GxEQZTj2qITwhpWd","MadW6eW3JIjnwAq5","cwwaFu2hLD2oCI96","79EEGzZ48cZiyOkD","iJDMvy9xPPKasEiT","xhA9bwdY7eKmTFwW","bmVGcgErU33NpcPe","051TTnNZLU1skKs7","0vsYAZPv719KiUtu","XAE3YbGvQQp3seS3"],"folderPath":["temp_okfc4yccund","temp_jtibz2gzdj"]}},"content":"","_id":"hquDquSBUYHILOcH"}
{"name":"Sorcerer","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.9oJEqxGPoymsbx7q"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>In a world where dragonmarked dynasties dominate the mystical economy, it’s easy to imagine how sorcerous bloodlines can fit into the world. What defines the sorcerer is the fact that their magic comes from within, that they must exert their will to coax the powers that lay dormant within them to manifest, whether it be from dragon’s blood, inherited power, the Mourning, the Daelkyr or being a product of Vadalis magebreeding.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Focus</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Gifted), Arcane Resistance, Improved Arcane Resistence, Charismatic, Elan</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Channeling, Concentration, Extra Effort, New Powers, Power Points, Power Surge, Soul Drain</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>","_id":"iJDMvy9xPPKasEiT"}
{"name":"Extend Range","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_53szy0z05dw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.3. Power Modifiers","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core\">\n<h3>Extend Range</h3>\n<p>Double the power&rsquo;s listed Range by taking a &minus;1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier}, or triple it for a &minus;1. This modifier may not be used on powers with a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Range]{Range} of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Touch Attack]{Touch} or the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Game Mastering]{Cone Template}.</p>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rituals]{Rituals}</h3>\n<p>Powers with a Range greater than Touch double their distance automatically when cast via @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rituals]{ritual}, as mentioned above, and powers with a Range or Touch or Self gain a Range of Smarts. The caster can double those ranges by taking an additional &minus;2 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier} or extend the Range to his Smarts die type in miles and ignore any sight restrictions by taking a &minus;4 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Casting Modifier}.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"jw01h7JHExJG4SEN"}
{"name":"Monk","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hUQGZcxPSlD3LK6T"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Beginning with a foundation of mental and physical discipline, a monk channels energy to force an impossible action to become possible, from moving with superhuman speed to striking with fists of flame. The monk focuses power within them and becomes a conduit with the strictest discipline.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics, Fighting, Faith or Psionics, Notice, Religion, Stealth</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles or Psionics), Fleet-Footed, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Counterattack, Improved Counterattack, Free Runner, Martial Artist, Martial Warrior</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Something</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Holy/Unholy Warrior</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Acrobat, Guardian, Holy Adept</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Chi, Danger Sense</p>","_id":"kDyEk332QR4nC4qr"}
{"name":"Magic","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_hcpgzvytjr6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. Magic","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<h2>Magic</h2>\n<p>Magic, and reliance upon magic, shapes and defines the societies of Eberron. For thousands of years, wizards, sorcerers, clerics, artificers, adepts, and magewrights have brought their magical talents to bear to solve the problems life poses. These solutions have helped humanoid society develop and thrive on every continent&mdash;particularly on Khorvaire. The result is a society suffused with magic. Skycoaches fly among the soaring towers of Sharn. Blacksmiths chant spells over forges to improve the way they work. Airships ferry passengers from Zilargo to Karrnath. Weavers draw threads of shadow into their fabrics. Streets are illuminated with magical light, and magic marks emblazon letters of credit and other important documents. Magic is in common use by professional spellcasters, though complex difficult magic is still rare and wondrous.</p>\n<p>All races have the capability for magic, though each has its own preference for the style and kind of magic. Mundane people my not understand how magic works, but they don't fear magic and often benefit from magical technology created by the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dragonmarks]{Dragonmarked Houses} (such as&nbsp;<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Everbright Lantern]{Everbright Lanterns}</em>&nbsp;or<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Feather Token]{Feather Tokens}</em>&nbsp;or witnessing the work of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Organizations in House Phiarlan]{Carnival of Shadows}).</p>\n<br />\n<h2>Articles on the Use of Magic</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Powers Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rituals]{Rituals}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/art/covers/magic-of-eberron.webp\" alt=\"Magical battle in Khyber against the daelkyr\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"modules/savage-eberron-artwork/assets/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","_id":"kd3FrhoheRqRUfQB"}
{"name":"Healer","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.OhgQJk3PFo6QpRC0"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>House Jorasco is known for its hospitals and healing services. During The Last War, they provided services to heal wounded soldiers on the battlefields. Some clerics heed the call to tend to the sick, those who cannot afford the costs of healing services otherwise. Among adventurers and explorers, healers provide a crucial service among their teams.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Healing, Herbalism, Science</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Healing or Herbal Alchemy)</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Herbal Mastery</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Healer</p>","_id":"kd8opJureBSMcoSR"}
{"name":"Necromancer","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.mMBVGTbi74PNwMup"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Necromancers learn to manipulate the energy that animates all living things. Most people see necromancers as menacing, or even villainous, due to the dose association with death. Not all necromancers are evil, but the forces they manipulate are considered taboo by many societies.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Lore, Religion, Spellcasting or Faith</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles or Magic)</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Familiar, Necromancer, Master Necromancer, Scholar</p>","_id":"lPUkD9iZnWVoGui1"}
{"name":"Paladin","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.w8MXUYWW2zi3Phyx"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>Like clerics, Paladins are the champions of the churches, most notably the Church of the Silver Flame and, in some cases, select churches of the Sovereign Host. Paladins follow an exalted life and are held to a higher standard than even clerics. Clerics can fall to corruption and still retain their abilities, but paladins are above the corruption that can infect a church and adhere to the highest ideals of their faiths.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics, Faith, Fighting, Healing, Persuasion, Riding</p>\n<p><strong>Hindrance:</strong> Code of Honor, Vow</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles), Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Any combat edge</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Any leadership edge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Guardian, Knight</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolster, Provoke, Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Champion</p>","_id":"ljQ8DjaXhuYgnc9y"}
{"name":"Chronicler","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.DmIr9SbZXF7Yu2ND"},"cf":{"id":"temp_vjikafm48ed","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<p>People need news, and you’re the one to provide it. You could be an investigative reporter searching for issues of national importance such as conspiracies, corruption, threats of war, or news about the Mourning. You could be gathering gossip, or sharing the tales of bold adventurers, so make sure your friends do something worthy of a story! You could also be a general agent of the Library of Korranberg, always watchful for anything that could expand the repository of general knowledge.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Research, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Linguist</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Something </p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Something</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Something </p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Entertainer, Investigator, Honey Tongue, Jack-of-all-Trades, Scholar</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Streetwise, Work the Room, Work the Crowd</p>","_id":"mEEAmdsvWqtD6hAy"}
